{"title_page": "WinRed", "text_new": "'''WinRed''' is a [[conservative]] fundraising platform endorsed by the [[Republican National Committee]] and [[Donald Trump]]. It was launched to compete with [[ActBlue]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] fundraising platform.\n\n==Product details==\nWinRed is a fundraising platform built for the Republican party.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Crabtree |first1=Susan |title=Backlash Ensues as RNC's WinRed Fundraising Hammer Falls |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2019/07/16/backlash_ensues_as_rncs_winred_fundraising_hammer_falls.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=RealClearPolitics |date=16 July 2019}}</ref> It was built to compete with the older Democrat platform [[ActBlue]]. The national Republican Party, the Trump re-election campaign, and other state- and local-level races across the United States used the platform as of late 2019.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Pappas |first1=Alex |title=WinRed, new GOP donor platform, reaps impeachment windfall, rakes in millions since probe launch |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/winred-impeachment-republican-donor-platform-windfall |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nWinRed merges Revv, a GOP payment processing firm founded by [[Gerrit AP NEWS (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]], and DataTrust, the party's voter data repository. The platform allows one-click donations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |title=GOP unveils fundraising tool to rival Democrats' ActBlue |url=https://apnews.com/f845d66c4dd94fb8ae2cd94a3c1aed40 |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=AP News |date=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Fox News]] notes that a contributing factor to Democratic success in the 2018 midterm elections was the party's ability to take in online small-dollar donations, in part through their platform [[ActBlue]]. WinRed was built to oppose this capacity.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" /> WinRed was called Patriot Pass in its initial announcements, with an expected release date of February 2019. However, the name was changed following Robert Krafts's complaints that the name resembled that of his football team, the Patriots.<ref name=\"NPR-RedShift-July2019\">{{cite news |last1=Overby |first1=Peter |title=Red Shift: How Republicans Plan To Catch Democrats In Online Fundraising |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/01/736990455/red-shift-how-republicans-plan-to-catch-democrats-in-online-fundraising |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=NPR |date=1 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Fundraising==\nIn the three months after launch, WinRed raised over $30 million, surpassing its goal of $20-25 million for the first quarter. [[Gerrit Lansing (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]] and Sam Miele, the founders of WinRed, as well as well as various Republican operatives, attributed some of this success to the impeachment effort at the time. In the day after announcement of impeachment, the Trump campaign and the RNC received over $5 million dollars.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" />\n\nIn its first six months, WinRed took in $100 million.<ref name=\"NYT-takeover-2020\">{{cite news |last1=Hakim |first1=Danny |last2=Thrush |first2=Glenn |title=How the Trump Campaign Took Over the G.O.P. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/us/trump-campaign-brad-parscale.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Competitors==\nIn October 2019, The Trump administration sent a cease-and-desist letter to formal rival [[Anedot]]. Any Republican candidate or official who uses Anedot or Give.GOP will no longer receive any support from the Republican Party.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States)]]\n", "text_old": "'''WinRed''' is a [[conservative]] fundraising platform endorsed by the [[Republican National Committee]] and [[Donald Trump]]. It was launched to compete with [[ActBlue]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] fundraising platform.\n\n==Product details==\nWinRed is a fundraising platform built for the Republican party.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Crabtree |first1=Susan |title=Backlash Ensues as RNC's WinRed Fundraising Hammer Falls |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2019/07/16/backlash_ensues_as_rncs_winred_fundraising_hammer_falls.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=RealClearPolitics |date=16 July 2019}}</ref> It was built to compete with the older Democrat platform [[ActBlue]]. The national Republican Party, the Trump re-election campaign, and other state- and local-level races across the United States used the platform as of late 2019.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Pappas |first1=Alex |title=WinRed, new GOP donor platform, reaps impeachment windfall, rakes in millions since probe launch |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/winred-impeachment-republican-donor-platform-windfall |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nWinRed merges Revv, a GOP payment processing firm founded by [[Gerrit AP NEWS (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]], and DataTrust, the party's voter data repository. The platform allows one-click donations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |title=GOP unveils fundraising tool to rival Democrats' ActBlue |url=https://apnews.com/f845d66c4dd94fb8ae2cd94a3c1aed40 |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=AP News |date=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Fox News]] notes that a contributing factor to Democratic success in the 2018 midterm elections was the party's ability to take in online small-dollar donations, in part through their platform [[ActBlue]]. WinRed was build to oppose this capacity.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" /> WinRed was called Patriot Pass in its initial announcements, with an expected release date of February 2019. However, the name was changed following Robert Krafts's complaints that the name resembled that of his football team, the Patriots.<ref name=\"NPR-RedShift-July2019\">{{cite news |last1=Overby |first1=Peter |title=Red Shift: How Republicans Plan To Catch Democrats In Online Fundraising |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/01/736990455/red-shift-how-republicans-plan-to-catch-democrats-in-online-fundraising |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=NPR |date=1 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Fundraising==\nIn the three months after launch, WinRed raised over $30 million, surpassing its goal of $20-25 million for the first quarter. [[Gerrit Lansing (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]] and Sam Miele, the founders of WinRed, as well as well as various Republican operatives, attributed some of this success to the impeachment effort at the time. In the day after announcement of impeachment, the Trump campaign and the RNC received over $5 million dollars.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" />\n\nIn its first six months, WinRed took in $100 million.<ref name=\"NYT-takeover-2020\">{{cite news |last1=Hakim |first1=Danny |last2=Thrush |first2=Glenn |title=How the Trump Campaign Took Over the G.O.P. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/us/trump-campaign-brad-parscale.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Competitors==\n[[Anedot]] (not limited to any one party) and Give.GOP are other major platforms in the Republican fundraising space.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States)]]\n", "name_user": "Readmore134", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (\"build\" to \"built\")", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WinRed"}
{"title_page": "Annika Duckmark", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish television presenter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n[[File:Annika Duckmark 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|Annika Duckmark, in 2009]]\n\n'''Annika Duckmark''', (born 17 September 1971 in [[Bor\u00e5s]], [[V\u00e4sterg\u00f6tland]], Sweden) is a Swedish television presenter. She was crowned as [[Miss Sweden]] in 1996.<ref>[http://www.sverigesman.se/historik/fr_sverige/genom_tiderna.htm Fr\u00f6ken Sverige genom tiderna] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821132501/http://www.sverigesman.se/historik/fr_sverige/genom_tiderna.htm |date=2010-08-21 }}, accessed 2010-05-19 {{in lang|sv}}</ref> \n\nDuckmark represented Sweden at the [[Miss Universe 1996]] where she was ranked 4th overall during the preliminary competition. This ranking enabled her to advance as one of the top 10 semifinalists, ultimately placing 10th overall during the semifinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/extra/annika-duckmark-det-var-tufft-och-jag-grat-mycket/|title=Annika Duckmark: \"Det var tufft och jag gr\u00e4t mycket\" - Extra - Expressen|website=Expressen|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-05-18-mn-5574-story,amp.html|title=Results of Miss Universe 1996|date=18 May 1996|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=18 April 2019|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Duckmark presented the movie-review show  \u201dWide screen\u201d on [[TV1000]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.cision.com/se/svenska-spel/r/annika-duckmark-ar-modellen-for-lotto,c20376|title=Annika Duckmark \u00e4r modellen f\u00f6r Lotto|website=News Powered by Cision|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\nDuckmark presented the Lotto draw on [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] each week from 2000 and onwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwwc.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/0009/07/lotto.html|title=Aftonbladet nyheter: Lotto firar 20-\u00e5rsjubileum|website=wwwc.aftonbladet.se|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/leva-och-bo/|title=Inredning, tips om m\u00f6bler, tr\u00e4dg\u00e5rd, heminredning, bygg|website=Leva och bo|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDuckmark was married to the former football player [[Tomas Brolin]] before they divorced in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hant.se/han-ar-froken-sverige-annika-duckmarks-nya-karlek/|title=Han \u00e4r Fr\u00f6ken Sverige-Annika Duckmarks nya k\u00e4rlek|date=2018-01-16|website=H\u00e4nt.se|language=sv-SE|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.npp-photo.com/Midlese-b6fslist.asp?Artal=1996/ Miss Sweden 1996]{{Dead link|date=September 2016}}\n\n{{Miss Universe 1996 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duckmark, Annika}}\n\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Miss Sweden winners]]\n[[Category:Miss Universe 1996 contestants]]\n[[Category:People from Bor\u00e5s]]\n[[Category:Swedish television personalities]]\n\n{{Europe-pageant-bio-stub}}\n{{Sweden-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish television presenter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n[[File:Annika Duckmark 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|Annika Duckmark, in 2009]]\n\n'''Annika Duckmark''', (born 17 September 1971 in [[Bor\u00e5s]], [[V\u00e4sterg\u00f6tland]], Sweden) is a Swedish television presenter. She was crowned as [[Miss Sweden]] in 1996.<ref>[http://www.sverigesman.se/historik/fr_sverige/genom_tiderna.htm Fr\u00f6ken Sverige genom tiderna] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821132501/http://www.sverigesman.se/historik/fr_sverige/genom_tiderna.htm |date=2010-08-21 }}, accessed 2010-05-19 {{in lang|sv}}</ref> \n\nDuckmark represented Sweden at the [[Miss Universe 1996]] where she was ranked 4th overall during the preliminary competition. This ranking enabled her to advance as one of the top 10 semifinalists, ultimately she placed 10th overall during the semifinalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/extra/annika-duckmark-det-var-tufft-och-jag-grat-mycket/|title=Annika Duckmark: \"Det var tufft och jag gr\u00e4t mycket\" - Extra - Expressen|website=Expressen|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-05-18-mn-5574-story,amp.html|title=Results of Miss Universe 1996|date=18 May 1996|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=18 April 2019|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Duckmark presented the movie-review show  \u201dWide screen\u201d on [[TV1000]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.cision.com/se/svenska-spel/r/annika-duckmark-ar-modellen-for-lotto,c20376|title=Annika Duckmark \u00e4r modellen f\u00f6r Lotto|website=News Powered by Cision|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\nDuckmark presented the Lotto draw on [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] each week from 2000 and onwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwwc.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/0009/07/lotto.html|title=Aftonbladet nyheter: Lotto firar 20-\u00e5rsjubileum|website=wwwc.aftonbladet.se|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/leva-och-bo/|title=Inredning, tips om m\u00f6bler, tr\u00e4dg\u00e5rd, heminredning, bygg|website=Leva och bo|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDuckmark was married to the former football player [[Tomas Brolin]] before they divorced in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hant.se/han-ar-froken-sverige-annika-duckmarks-nya-karlek/|title=Han \u00e4r Fr\u00f6ken Sverige-Annika Duckmarks nya k\u00e4rlek|date=2018-01-16|website=H\u00e4nt.se|language=sv-SE|access-date=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.npp-photo.com/Midlese-b6fslist.asp?Artal=1996/ Miss Sweden 1996]{{Dead link|date=September 2016}}\n\n{{Miss Universe 1996 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duckmark, Annika}}\n\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Miss Sweden winners]]\n[[Category:Miss Universe 1996 contestants]]\n[[Category:People from Bor\u00e5s]]\n[[Category:Swedish television personalities]]\n\n{{Europe-pageant-bio-stub}}\n{{Sweden-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kylayujiri", "label": "safe", "comment": "Edited sentence for grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annika_Duckmark"}
{"title_page": "Robert Lauder of the Bass", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{For|the 16th century land magnate|Robert Lauder (land magnate)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n\n'''Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass''' (before 1440 \u2013 c. January 1508) was a Scottish knight, [[armiger]], and Governor of the Castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]]. He was also a member of the old Scottish Parliament.<ref>Young, James, ''Historical References to the Scottish Family of Lauder'' (Glasgow, 1884), p. 90</ref> The Lauders held the feudal barony of [[The Bass]] (the caput of which was its castle), [[East Lothian]], [[Edrington Castle]] and lands in the parish of [[Mordington]], Berwickshire, [[Tyninghame]] in Haddingtonshire, and numerous other estates and properties elsewhere in [[Scotland]].\n\n== Robert of Edrington ==\n\nLauder was the eldest son and heir of Robert Lauder of the Bass (d.1495) by his first spouse Jonet,<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref> daughter of [[Alexander Home, 1st Lord Home|Sir Alexander Home]]<ref>Dunlop, A.I., MacLauchlan, David, Cowan, Ian, editors, ''Calendar of Scottish Supplications to Rome 1433\u20131447'', vol. 4 (Glasgow Press, 1983), no. 885: 219</ref>\n\nPrior to his father's death, Lauder was usually designated \"of [[Edrington]]\" in Berwickshire.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 25 April 1450: 343</ref> After his purchase of the lands of [[Biel, East Lothian|Biell]], in East Lothian he was designated 'of Biel'.\n\nIn 1462 [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] was recovered by the Scots and Lauder was put in charge of [[Berwick Castle]], until he was succeeded in 1474 by [[David Lindsay, 1st Duke of Montrose|David, Earl of Crawford]]. In 1464 Lauder was paid \u00a320 for repairs to the castle.<ref>Scott, John, ''Berwick-upon-Tweed, The History of the Town and Guild'', London, 1888</ref>\n\nA notorial instrument dated 13 May 1465 narrates:<blockquote>[this] Robert Lauder, son and apparent heir of Sir Robert Lauder of Edrington, asserted that David Lauder of Popil ([[East Lothian]]) had given sasine and heritable possession to his eldest son James Lauder and Jonete his spouse, their heirs etc., of a certain piece of land at Popil, to the prejudice of the first-mentioned Robert, who solemnly protested that the said sasine should neither be valid nor prejudice his right in the land, and for greater security, he, by throwing of earth and stone outside the house belonging to the piece of land, and by breaking a plate with his foot, broke and annulled the said sasine and so possession by James Lauder and his wife. Done at Popil at 7 a.m. on 13th May 1465 before Henry Ogil of Popil, James Ogil his eldest son, and others.</blockquote>\n\n\"Robert de Laweder de Edryngtoun\" is the first witness to a Retour of Service, dated 7 April 1467, of Margaret Sinclair as one of the heirs of her grandfather John Sinclair in the lands of Kimmerghame, Berwickshire.<ref>Historic Manuscripts Commission, ''Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne-Home of Wedderburn Castle, N.B.'', London, 1902: 258</ref> Although he was not yet in formal possession of the Edrington estate (see next entry below) he appears to be regularly using the designation, as eldest son, 'of Edrington'.\n\n==Invested in Edrington==\n\nIn a charter of 1471, [[James III of Scotland]] confirmed to Robert Lauder, son and heir apparent of Robert Lauder of Edrington and the Bass, the lands of Edrington and Coalstell with the fishings of Edermouth (or mouth of the [[Whiteadder Water]]) plus the mill there (at Edrington) which Robert the father personally resigned to Robert junior and his male heirs failing which those relations bearing the Lauder arms.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref>\n\nIn a further charter signed at [[Edinburgh]] on 26 June 1474 and confirmed there on 27 July 1475, James III confirmed a feu charter of Robert Lauder junior, Lord of Edringtoun, and superior of West Nisbet, to David Creichtoun of Cranstoun and his heirs, of the lands of West Nisbet in the barony of [[Pencaitland]], East Lothian, which John de Colquhoun of Luss has resigned into the said Robert Lauder junior's hands. Witnesses included Robert Lauder of Bass, father of said Robert junior, and a William Lauder.<ref>''The Great Seal'', 1477: 1202/1299</ref>\n\n==Governor of Berwick castle==\n\nKing [[James III of Scotland]] again appointed Robert Lauder of Edrington as custodian and governor of the castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] for 5 years, with a retainer of 200 merks per annum.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 20 January 1477: 1276</ref>\n\nIn 1477 Robert was one of those entrusted by James III to escort the dowry of Princess [[Cecily of York]] for her planned marriage to [[James IV of Scotland|James, Duke of Rothesay]]. Cecily was the third daughter of [[Edward IV of England]] and [[Elizabeth Woodville]].\n\nBain records that on 2 February 1477: \"James King of Scotland signifies to the bearers of the instalment of the Princess Cecilia's dower due at [[Candlemas]]s, that he has sent Alexander, Lord Hume, Robert of Lawdir of Edrington son and heir apparent to Robert of Lawdir of the Bass, and Adam of Blackadder of that Ilk, with the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]], to conduct them to Edinburgh.\"\n\nA charter of 1477 to Alexander Inglis of tenements of land in Hide Hill etc., in [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], lists those who own neighbouring properties, which include \"Robert Lauder of Bass junior\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 3 March 1477: 1281</ref>\n\n===Other mentions===\n\nA Retour of Special Service was held at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] on 20 May 1477 serving Thomas Broun (of lawful age) as son and heir to John Broun (who has been dead three months), in a carucate of land with pertinents on the north side of Flemington, (near [[Eyemouth]], Berwickshire), valued at four merks annually and held in chief of the Laird of [[Restalrig]] [near Edinburgh] and Flemington for service of ward and relief, such services being given as neighbouring tenants in these lands are accustomed to give. Retour given by Henry Congiltoun, Sheriff depute of Berwick. Amongst the jury was Robert Lawder of Edrington, Thomas Edingtoun of that Ilk, Thomas Lumsden of that Ilk, William Douglas, Archibald Manderston, John Skougall and William Lauder.\n\nHe witnessed a charter at the castle of [[Dunbar]] on 18 December 1475 as \"Robert Lauder of Edrington\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 27 July 1479: 1428</ref> On 2 April 1486, a \"Robert Lawedar\" was one of the witnesses to document signed on the High Altar at [[Holyrood Abbey]]. As the leading witness was William Hall, Vicar of [[Bara, East Lothian|Baro]], it is probable that this Robert is of the Bass family. Another witness was an Alexander Home.\n\nIn 1489 [[James IV of Scotland]] granted a charter to Lauder of the lands of Beil, Johnscleuch in the [[Lammermuir Hills]], and \"le Clyntis\", with their towers and mills etc., in the Barony of Dunbar, formerly owned by Hugo de Dunbar & Beil, with the lands and mill of Mersington, Berwickshire, which Hugo de Dunbar of Bele also resigned. The charter mentions Robert's wife Isabel Hay.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 12 September 1489: 1894</ref>\n\nThe''[[Exchequer Rolls]]'' record Robert Lauder of Edrington in possession of the lands of Glensax in Yarrow, [[Selkirkshire]] in 1489/1490/1491.\n\n== Papal petition ==\n\nA Petition to [[Pope Innocent VIII]] signed in the presence of Henry Congleton and others in January 1491, craved absolution for numerous people during the 'recent troubles' in Scotland and the [[Battle of Sauchieburn]] (11 June 1488). Lauder was named as son and heir of the Lord of Bass and Baron of [[Stenton]]. Others include Kentigern Hepburn of Waughtoun, Patrick Skowgale, Alexander Sidserf, William Sinclair, David Renton of Billie & [[Lamberton, Berwickshire|Lamberton]], Alexander Home, Archibald Dunbar, William Manderston, Gavin Home, and John Sommerville.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), 263\u20134.</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 1494 in a court held at Stenton, before John Swinton of that Ilk, depute and lieutenant of John, [[Lord Glamis]], and Robert Lord l'Isle, King's Justiciars generally constituted from the south side of the Forth; Robert Lauder of Bass showed a charter or writ of resignation by the deceased Gilbery Duchry mentioning that Gilbert resigned the land or tenement of Duchry (in the [[Lammermuir Hills]]), in the tenement of Stentoun, in the hands of Walter, Stewart of Scotland, superior thereof. Robert Lauder of Beil, son and apparent heir of the said Robert, asserted that a charter by his father to him of the mains of [[Stenton]] and three-quarters of the town and territory made no reservation of the lands of Duchry. The witnesses were Robert Laweder, son and apparent heir of Robert Lauder of Beill, James Cockburn of [[Clerkington]], William Hepburn of [[Athelstaneford]], Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, James Ogill, David Ogill, and others.{{cn}}\n\n==Death of father==\n\nRobert Lauder was granted sasine of Stenton, Garvald, and The Bass in 1495,<ref>''Exchequer Rolls''</ref> and the lands of Symprin and Ladypart, near Lauder. This would normally occur upon the death of the head of the family.\n\nA charter registered (but almost certainly signed much earlier) on 1 February 1497 records \"Robert Lauder of Bass and Lord of Auldkathi to Robert Lauder his eldest son and Ysobella [sic] Hay his spouse, and their survivor of them, and their heirs male to be procreated of their bodies, of the lands of Auldkathi lying in the barony of Kynnele ([[Kinnoull]]) and sheriffdom of (Lin)Lithgow. Witnesses were William Hay of Menzen, William Hay of Tallo, Hugh of Dunbar, Gavin Lumsden, Thomas and Peter Wood and James Sinclair.\" The footnote states that the granter's seal is in fair condition.<ref>''Calendar of Writs preserved at Yester House'', Scottish Record Society: 240</ref>\n\n==Visit of James IV==\n\nIn 1497 King James IV visited the Bass\".<ref>John J. Reid, ''Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries'', 1885.</ref> The boatmen who conveyed him from [[Dunbar]] were paid 14 shillings.<ref>Phillimore, R.P., ''North Berwick, Gullane, Aberlady and East Linton District'' (North Berwick, 1913), p. 50.</ref> Robert was knighted after January 1497 but before July 1498, so probably on the occasion of the King's visit to the Bass.{{cn}}\n\n==Legal transactions==\n\nOn 10 July 1498, he raised an action as assignee to the deceased David Dunbar of Bele [Beil], heir of the deceased Alexander Dunbar of Biel, against Mungo Home, son and heir of the deceased John Home of Whiterig, [[Berwickshire]], and Margaret Hume his mother, for postponing and delaying to resign the 12 merk lands of the west end of Mersington, Berwickshire, with pertinents, \"land on the west half of the burne\" and keeping the charters and muniments thereof. The defenders did not appear. The Lords discern them to conform to the reversion produced, and assign 15 January next to the pursuer to prove the value of damages and violated profits and duties.{{cn}}\n\nIn July 1501 there was a dispute between Jonet, prioress of the Convent of [[Haddington, East Lothian|Haddington]], (represented by David Balfour of Caraldstone) and Robert Lauder of the Bass, knight, regarding the lands and chapellany of [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]], East Lothian, and also damage made to Lauder's house at [[White Castle, East Lothian|Whitecastle]] (or Nunraw) near Haddington. At the second hearing Robert was present in person. The case was referred to [[Patrick Hepburn, 1st Earl of Bothwell]], for his consideration and adjourned until 15 October 1501.<ref>James Clyde, ''Acta Dominorum Concilii'' (Edinburgh, 1943), nos 230, 233 and 326.</ref>\n\nThe King confirmed a charter signed on [[the Bass]] on 12 July 1502 of Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott to Robert Lawdir of Bass of the lands of Wester Spott, Gryndanehede and The Newkis in [[Haddingtonshire]], reserving the usual [[liferent]]s for the granter. Witnesses included Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, Henry Congiltoun of that Ilk, and Kentigern Hepburn of Lufnes [and Waughtoun].<ref>''Register of the Great Seal'', 1502, number 2659.</ref>\n\nSubsequent to that, on 3 January 1503/1504, Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott renounced his liferent interest in those properties, the renunciation 'done in the burgh of Edinburgh, in the tenement of Mr.Richard Lawson of Hierriggs, in his close thereof.'  Letters of Procuratory were signed at Beil on 6 August 1504, by Robert Lawder addressed to James IV informing him that he (Robert) had appointed Richard Lawson of Hieriggs, [[Lord Justice Clerk]], James Henderson and Richard Bothwell, John Homyll and David Anderson, as procurators, for resigning his lands of Wester Spott, Gryndenhede, and 'le Snyke,' with pertinents, into the hands of the King as superior.{{cn}}\n\nPatrick Scougal of that Ilk had a tack [lease] of a quarter of the lands of [[Auldhame]], near [[North Berwick]], from George Home of Spott, with an agreement that it would later be feued to him. Agreed and signed at Beil on 26 September 1504, with Sir Robert Lawedir of the Bass one of the witnesses.{{cn}}\n\nLauder owned property on the [[Royal Mile|High Street]] of [[Edinburgh]], mentioned in a letter of reversion dated 16 April 1505 by Mr John of Murray, burgess of Edinburgh to William of Todrig, burgess of Edinburgh, of an annual rent of 40s Scots out of the houses and land called \"the paintit chalmer\" with the pertinents lying in the said burgh on the north side of the King's Street between the lands of Sir William Lindsay on the east part and the land of the Archbishop of Glasgow on the west part and the land of William Halkerstoune [Haxton] on the south part and the land of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass on the north part.<ref>National Archives of Scotland GD32/21/3.</ref>\n\n== Pilgrimage ==\n\nIn 1506 Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass went on a pilgrimage to pray at the shrine of St.John of [[Amiens]], accompanied by a large retinue of family and friends.\n\nOn 10 May 1506, at [[Edinburgh]], \"A Lettre of Licence [was] maid to Robert Lawder of the Bass, knycht, his men, servandis, and inhabitantis his landis, Robert Lawder, his son and apperand aire, John Swyntoun of that ilk, Johne Swytoun, his son and apperand aire, Robert Lawder of the Tower of Lawder, Alexander Cockburn of Newhall, Gilbert Wauchop in Howstoun, Alexander Sideserff of that Ilk, George Lile of Stonypath (nr. [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]]), David Lawder of Popill, Johne Forestare of Gammilschelis, Henry Congiltoun of that ilk, Thomas Wod of the Grange, William Gibson and Peter Wod in Akansid, and als all the saidis Robertis and thare tennandis, familiaris, servandis, procuratoris, attornais, factouris and intromettouris, and all and sundri his and thare gudis, rentis, possessionis, annuellis, fermez, etc., for the passing of the said Robert to Sanct Johne of Ameas [Amiens], in his pilgrimage, and uther partis bezond sey in his erandis: And Als respittis him and all the persounis above written, thair tennandis, etc., for all actiounis concernyn the kingis grace, etc., to ceis fra the day of the date hereof quhill his hamecummyn and forty dayis thairefter: And attour exempand the said Robert and all the persouns abone writtin fra the compering to ony parliamentis, justice-airis, chawmerlane-aires schireff courtis and ony uther courtis for ony maner of actiouns concernyn the kingis grace enduring the tyme forsaid.\"<ref>''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1257, pp. 181-2.</ref>\nIt seems clear that those named in this License have feus of certain properties from Sir Robert.{{cn}} Certainly Popill, and Newhall [Lothians], were owned by the lairds of Bass. What is also clear is that the Robert Lauder at [[Lauder]] Tower, Berwickshire, is not the son and heir of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass, but a separate entity.{{cn}}\n\nA Letter of Licence was given to Lauder to [give?] 'analy' [annually?] four merks worth of land of aul [old] extent of his lands of Ladypart, lying in the bailiary of Lawderdale, sheriffdom of Berwick, to what person or persons he pleases. Dated at Edinburgh 27 October 1506.{{cn}}\n\nOn 1 February 1508 Sasine was granted to his son, also Robert, of [[the Bass]] and other holdings.<ref>''Exchequer Rolls of Scotland''.</ref> It is assumed Sir Robert died shortly before this date.\n\n== Marriage and descendants ==\n\nRobert Lauder married sometime before 1489 Isabella Hay, daughter of [[John Hay, 1st Lord Hay of Yester]]. She was a descendant of [[Robert I of Scotland|Robert The Bruce]], and a great-great granddaughter of [[Robert III of Scotland|Robert III]].\n\nOf their children:\n* Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass (d. 1517/18).\n* William Lauder, from whom descend the [[Belhaven, Scotland|Belhaven]] and West Barns branch of this family<ref>Lawder, C.A.B.,''The Lawders of the Bass & their descendants'' (Belfast, 1914).</ref><ref>Fleming, D. Hay, and Beveridge, James, ''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1542\u20131548'', vol 3 (Edinburgh, 1936), no. 1063: 167</ref> including [[Sir Robert Lauder of Beilmouth]].\n* Agnes Lauder, married Alexander Cockburn of Newhall.<ref>Cockburn-Hood, Thomas H, ''House of Cockburn'' (Edinburgh, 1888), p. 264.</ref>\n* Elizabeth Lauder, married before October 1506, David Renton of Billie, & Lamberton.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), no.500: 227</ref>\n* Margaret, married (1) before September 1498, Kentigern Hepburn of Waughton and Lufness (d. July 1519),<ref>Hepburn, Edward, ''Genealogical Notes of the Hepburn Family'' (1925), 32.</ref> (2) 23 January 1521 (date of Papal Dispensation) Alexander Hume of [[Polwarth, Scottish Borders|Polwarth]], Berwickshire, who died May 1532 when she was still living.<ref>''The Humes of Polwarth'' (Edinburgh, 1894), pp. 179\u2013180</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n* ''Protocol Book of James Young'', [[Scottish Record Society]], Edinburgh, numbers 726, 1392, and 1468.\n* ''Exchequer Rolls: 1488\u20131496'', edited by George Burnett, vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1887),  , pps: 652, 679, 770\u20131, & 738.\n* ''Calendar of Documents relating to Scotland: 1357\u20131509'', edited by Joseph Bain, volume 4 (Edinburgh, 1888), number 1445.\n* ''The Grange of St.Giles'', by J.Stewart Smith, (Edinburgh, 1898).\n* ''Calendar of the Laing Charters, AD 854-1837'', edited by the Rev.John Anderson, (Edinburgh, 1899), numbers 64 (p.&nbsp;250), 196 (p.&nbsp;50), and p.&nbsp;153.\n* ''The Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529,'', vol. 1,  edited by M. Livingstone, (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1349, p.&nbsp;192.\n* ''The Berwick & East Lothian Coasts'', by Ian C. Hannah, (London, 1913), p.&nbsp;29).\n* ''Acts of the Lords of Council in Civil Causes, 1496 \u2013 1501'', volume II, page 261.\n* ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage'', edited by Peter Townend, 105th edition, (London, 1970), p.&nbsp;2687.\n* ''The Lauders of the Bass'', by G. M. S. Lauder-Frost, in ''East Lothian Life'', Autumn 1996, issue 22, {{ISSN|1361-7818}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauder, Robert, Of The Bass}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Category:1508 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish knights]]\n[[Category:People from East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Scottish soldiers]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 Parliament of Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{For|the 16th century land magnate|Robert Lauder (land magnate)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n\n'''Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass''' (before 1440 \u2013 c. January 1508) was a Scottish knight, [[armiger]], and Governor of the Castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]]. He was also a member of the old Scottish Parliament.<ref>Young, James, ''Historical References to the Scottish Family of Lauder'' (Glasgow, 1884), p. 90</ref> The Lauders held the feudal barony of [[The Bass]] (the caput of which was its castle), [[East Lothian]], [[Edrington Castle]] and lands in the parish of [[Mordington]], Berwickshire, [[Tyninghame]] in Haddingtonshire, and numerous other estates and properties elsewhere in [[Scotland]].\n\n== Robert of Edrington ==\n\nLauder was the eldest son and heir of Robert Lauder of the Bass (d.1495) by his first spouse Jonet,<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref> daughter of [[Alexander Home, 1st Lord Home|Sir Alexander Home]]<ref>Dunlop, A.I., MacLauchlan, David, Cowan, Ian, editors, ''Calendar of Scottish Supplications to Rome 1433\u20131447'', vol. 4 (Glasgow Press, 1983), no. 885: 219</ref>\n\nPrior to his father's death, Lauder was usually designated \"of [[Edrington]]\" in Berwickshire.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 25 April 1450: 343</ref> After his purchase of the lands of [[Biel, East Lothian|Biell]], in East Lothian he was designated 'of Biel'.\n\nIn 1462 [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] was recovered by the Scots and Lauder was put in charge of [[Berwick Castle]], until he was succeeded in 1474 by [[David Lindsay, 1st Duke of Montrose|David, Earl of Crawford]]. In 1464 Lauder was paid \u00a320 for repairs to the castle.<ref>Scott, John, ''Berwick-upon-Tweed, The History of the Town and Guild'', London, 1888</ref>\n\nA notorial instrument dated 13 May 1465 narrates:<blockquote>[this] Robert Lauder, son and apparent heir of Sir Robert Lauder of Edrington, asserted that David Lauder of Popil ([[East Lothian]]) had given sasine and heritable possession to his eldest son James Lauder and Jonete his spouse, their heirs etc., of a certain piece of land at Popil, to the prejudice of the first-mentioned Robert, who solemnly protested that the said sasine should neither be valid nor prejudice his right in the land, and for greater security, he, by throwing of earth and stone outside the house belonging to the piece of land, and by breaking a plate with his foot, broke and annulled the said sasine and so possession by James Lauder and his wife. Done at Popil at 7 a.m. on 13th May 1465 before Henry Ogil of Popil, James Ogil his eldest son, and others.</blockquote>\n\n\"Robert de Laweder de Edryngtoun\" is the first witness to a Retour of Service, dated 7 April 1467, of Margaret Sinclair as one of the heirs of her grandfather John Sinclair in the lands of Kimmerghame, Berwickshire.<ref>Historic Manuscripts Commission, ''Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne-Home of Wedderburn Castle, N.B.'', London, 1902: 258</ref> Although he was not yet in formal possession of the Edrington estate (see next entry below) he appears to be regularly using the designation, as eldest son, 'of Edrington'.\n\n==Invested in Edrington==\n\nIn a charter of 1471, [[James III of Scotland]] confirmed to Robert Lauder, son and heir apparent of Robert Lauder of Edrington and the Bass, the lands of Edrington and Coalstell with the fishings of Edermouth (or mouth of the [[Whiteadder Water]]) plus the mill there (at Edrington) which Robert the father personally resigned to Robert junior and his male heirs failing which those relations bearing the Lauder arms.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref>\n\nIn a further charter signed at [[Edinburgh]] on 26 June 1474 and confirmed there on 27 July 1475, James III confirmed a feu charter of Robert Lauder junior, Lord of Edringtoun, and superior of West Nisbet, to David Creichtoun of Cranstoun and his heirs, of the lands of West Nisbet in the barony of [[Pencaitland]], East Lothian, which John de Colquhoun of Luss has resigned into the said Robert Lauder junior's hands. Witnesses included Robert Lauder of Bass, father of said Robert junior, and a William Lauder.<ref>''The Great Seal'', 1477: 1202/1299</ref>\n\n==Governor of Berwick castle==\n\nKing [[James III of Scotland]] again appointed Robert Lauder of Edrington as custodian and governor of the castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] for 5 years, with a retainer of 200 merks per annum.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 20 January 1477: 1276</ref>\n\nIn 1477 Robert was one of those entrusted by James III to escort the dowry of Princess [[Cecily of York]] for her planned marriage to [[James IV of Scotland|James, Duke of Rothesay]]. Cecily was the third daughter of [[Edward IV of England]] and [[Elizabeth Woodville]].\n\nBain records that on 2 February 1477: \"James King of Scotland signifies to the bearers of the instalment of the Princess Cecilia's dower due at [[Candlemas]]s, that he has sent Alexander, Lord Hume, Robert of Lawdir of Edrington son and heir apparent to Robert of Lawdir of the Bass, and Adam of Blackadder of that Ilk, with the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]], to conduct them to Edinburgh.\"\n\nA charter of 1477 to Alexander Inglis of tenements of land in Hide Hill etc., in [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], lists those who own neighbouring properties, which include \"Robert Lauder of Bass junior\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 3 March 1477: 1281</ref>\n\n===Other mentions===\n\nA Retour of Special Service was held at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] on 20 May 1477 serving Thomas Broun (of lawful age) as son and heir to John Broun (who has been dead three months), in a carucate of land with pertinents on the north side of Flemington, (near [[Eyemouth]], Berwickshire), valued at four merks annually and held in chief of the Laird of [[Restalrig]] [near Edinburgh] and Flemington for service of ward and relief, such services being given as neighbouring tenants in these lands are accustomed to give. Retour given by Henry Congiltoun, Sheriff depute of Berwick. Amongst the jury was Robert Lawder of Edrington, Thomas Edingtoun of that Ilk, Thomas Lumsden of that Ilk, William Douglas, Archibald Manderston, John Skougall and William Lauder.\n\nHe witnessed a charter at the castle of [[Dunbar]] on 18 December 1475 as \"Robert Lauder of Edrington\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 27 July 1479: 1428</ref> On 2 April 1486, a \"Robert Lawedar\" was one of the witnesses to document signed on the High Altar at [[Holyrood Abbey]]. As the leading witness was William Hall, Vicar of [[Bara, East Lothian|Baro]], it is probable that this Robert is of the Bass family. Another witness was an Alexander Home.\n\nIn 1489 [[James IV of Scotland]] granted a charter to Lauder of the lands of Beil, Johnscleuch in the [[Lammermuir Hills]], and \"le Clyntis\", with their towers and mills etc., in the Barony of Dunbar, formerly owned by Hugo de Dunbar & Beil, with the lands and mill of Mersington, Berwickshire, which Hugo de Dunbar of Bele also resigned. The charter mentions Robert's wife Isabel Hay.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 12 September 1489: 1894</ref>\n\nThe''[[Exchequer Rolls]]'' record Robert Lauder of Edrington in possession of the lands of Glensax in Yarrow, [[Selkirkshire]] in 1489/1490/1491.\n\n== Papal petition ==\n\nA Petition to [[Pope Innocent VIII]] signed in the presence of Henry Congleton and others in January 1491, craved absolution for numerous people during the 'recent troubles' in Scotland and the [[Battle of Sauchieburn]] (11 June 1488). Lauder was named as son and heir of the Lord of Bass and Baron of [[Stenton]]. Others include Kentigern Hepburn of Waughtoun, Patrick Skowgale, Alexander Sidserf, William Sinclair, David Renton of Billie & [[Lamberton, Berwickshire|Lamberton]], Alexander Home, Archibald Dunbar, William Manderston, Gavin Home, and John Sommerville.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), 263\u20134.</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 1494 in a court held at Stenton, before John Swinton of that Ilk, depute and lieutenant of John, [[Lord Glamis]], and Robert Lord l'Isle, King's Justiciars generally constituted from the south side of the Forth; Robert Lauder of Bass showed a charter or writ of resignation by the deceased Gilbery Duchry mentioning that Gilbert resigned the land or tenement of Duchry (in the [[Lammermuir Hills]]), in the tenement of Stentoun, in the hands of Walter, Stewart of Scotland, superior thereof. Robert Lauder of Beil, son and apparent heir of the said Robert, asserted that a charter by his father to him of the mains of [[Stenton]] and three-quarters of the town and territory made no reservation of the lands of Duchry. The witnesses were Robert Laweder, son and apparent heir of Robert Lauder of Beill, James Cockburn of [[Clerkington]], William Hepburn of [[Athelstaneford]], Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, James Ogill, David Ogill, and others.{{cn}}\n\n==Death of father==\n\nRobert Lauder was granted sasine of Stenton, Garvald, and The Bass in 1495,<ref>''Exchequer Rolls''</ref> and the lands of Symprin and Ladypart, near Lauder. This would normally occur upon the death of the head of the family.\n\nA charter registered (but almost certainly signed much earlier) on 1 February 1497 records \"Robert Lauder of Bass and Lord of Auldkathi to Robert Lauder his eldest son and Ysobella [sic] Hay his spouse, and their survivor of them, and their heirs male to be procreated of their bodies, of the lands of Auldkathi lying in the barony of Kynnele ([[Kinnoull]]) and sheriffdom of (Lin)Lithgow. Witnesses were William Hay of Menzen, William Hay of Tallo, Hugh of Dunbar, Gavin Lumsden, Thomas and Peter Wood and James Sinclair.\" The footnote states that the granter's seal is in fair condition.<ref>''Calendar of Writs preserved at Yester House'', Scottish Record Society: 240</ref>\n\n==Visit of James IV==\n\nIn 1497 King James IV visited the Bass\".<ref>John J. Reid, ''Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries'', 1885.</ref> The boatmen who conveyed him from [[Dunbar]] were paid 14 shillings.<ref>Phillimore, R.P., ''North Berwick, Gullane, Aberlady and East Linton District'' (North Berwick, 1913), p. 50.</ref> Robert was knighted after January 1497 but before July 1498, so probably on the occasion of the King's visit to the Bass.{{cn}}\n\n==Legal transactions==\n\nOn 10 July 1498, he raised an action as assignee to the deceased David Dunbar of Bele [Beil], heir of the deceased Alexander Dunbar of Biel, against Mungo Home, son and heir of the deceased John Home of Whiterig, [[Berwickshire]], and Margaret Hume his mother, for postponing and delaying to resign the 12 merk lands of the west end of Mersington, Berwickshire, with pertinents, \"land on the west half of the burne\" and keeping the charters and muniments thereof. The defenders did not appear. The Lords discern them to conform to the reversion produced, and assign 15 January next to the pursuer to prove the value of damages and violated profits and duties.{{cn}}\n\nIn July 1501 there was a dispute between Jonet, prioress of the Convent of [[Haddington, East Lothian|Haddington]], (represented by David Balfour of Caraldstone) and Robert Lauder of the Bass, knight, regarding the lands and chapellany of [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]], East Lothian, and also damage made to Lauder's house at [[White Castle, East Lothian|Whitecastle]] (or Nunraw) near Haddington. At the second hearing Robert was present in person. The case was referred to [[Patrick Hepburn, 1st Earl of Bothwell]], for his consideration and adjourned until 15 October 1501.<ref>James Clyde, ''Acta Dominorum Concilii'' (Edinburgh, 1943), nos 230, 233 and 326.</ref>\n\nThe King confirmed a charter signed on [[the Bass]] on 12 July 1502 of Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott to Robert Lawdir of Bass of the lands of Wester Spott, Gryndanehede and The Newkis in [[Haddingtonshire]], reserving the usual [[liferent]]s for the granter. Witnesses included Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, Henry Congiltoun of that Ilk, and Kentigern Hepburn of Lufnes [and Waughtoun].<ref>''Register of the Great Seal'', 1502, number 2659.<ref>\n\nSubsequent to that, on 3 January 1503/1504, Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott renounced his liferent interest in those properties, the renunciation 'done in the burgh of Edinburgh, in the tenement of Mr.Richard Lawson of Hierriggs, in his close thereof.'  Letters of Procuratory were signed at Beil on 6 August 1504, by Robert Lawder addressed to James IV informing him that he (Robert) had appointed Richard Lawson of Hieriggs, [[Lord Justice Clerk]], James Henderson and Richard Bothwell, John Homyll and David Anderson, as procurators, for resigning his lands of Wester Spott, Gryndenhede, and 'le Snyke,' with pertinents, into the hands of the King as superior.{{cn}}\n\nPatrick Scougal of that Ilk had a tack [lease] of a quarter of the lands of [[Auldhame]], near [[North Berwick]], from George Home of Spott, with an agreement that it would later be feued to him. Agreed and signed at Beil on 26 September 1504, with Sir Robert Lawedir of the Bass one of the witnesses.{{cn}}\n\nLauder owned property on the [[Royal Mile|High Street]] of [[Edinburgh]], mentioned in a letter of reversion dated 16 April 1505 by Mr John of Murray, burgess of Edinburgh to William of Todrig, burgess of Edinburgh, of an annual rent of 40s Scots out of the houses and land called \"the paintit chalmer\" with the pertinents lying in the said burgh on the north side of the King's Street between the lands of Sir William Lindsay on the east part and the land of the Archbishop of Glasgow on the west part and the land of William Halkerstoune [Haxton] on the south part and the land of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass on the north part.<ref>National Archives of Scotland GD32/21/3.</ref>\n\n== Pilgrimage ==\n\nIn 1506 Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass went on a pilgrimage to pray at the shrine of St.John of [[Amiens]], accompanied by a large retinue of family and friends.\n\nOn 10 May 1506, at [[Edinburgh]], \"A Lettre of Licence [was] maid to Robert Lawder of the Bass, knycht, his men, servandis, and inhabitantis his landis, Robert Lawder, his son and apperand aire, John Swyntoun of that ilk, Johne Swytoun, his son and apperand aire, Robert Lawder of the Tower of Lawder, Alexander Cockburn of Newhall, Gilbert Wauchop in Howstoun, Alexander Sideserff of that Ilk, George Lile of Stonypath (nr. [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]]), David Lawder of Popill, Johne Forestare of Gammilschelis, Henry Congiltoun of that ilk, Thomas Wod of the Grange, William Gibson and Peter Wod in Akansid, and als all the saidis Robertis and thare tennandis, familiaris, servandis, procuratoris, attornais, factouris and intromettouris, and all and sundri his and thare gudis, rentis, possessionis, annuellis, fermez, etc., for the passing of the said Robert to Sanct Johne of Ameas [Amiens], in his pilgrimage, and uther partis bezond sey in his erandis: And Als respittis him and all the persounis above written, thair tennandis, etc., for all actiounis concernyn the kingis grace, etc., to ceis fra the day of the date hereof quhill his hamecummyn and forty dayis thairefter: And attour exempand the said Robert and all the persouns abone writtin fra the compering to ony parliamentis, justice-airis, chawmerlane-aires schireff courtis and ony uther courtis for ony maner of actiouns concernyn the kingis grace enduring the tyme forsaid.\"<ref>''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1257, pp. 181-2.</ref>\nIt seems clear that those named in this License have feus of certain properties from Sir Robert.{{cn}} Certainly Popill, and Newhall [Lothians], were owned by the lairds of Bass. What is also clear is that the Robert Lauder at [[Lauder]] Tower, Berwickshire, is not the son and heir of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass, but a separate entity.{{cn}}\n\nA Letter of Licence was given to Lauder to [give?] 'analy' [annually?] four merks worth of land of aul [old] extent of his lands of Ladypart, lying in the bailiary of Lawderdale, sheriffdom of Berwick, to what person or persons he pleases. Dated at Edinburgh 27 October 1506.{{cn}}\n\nOn 1 February 1508 Sasine was granted to his son, also Robert, of [[the Bass]] and other holdings.<ref>''Exchequer Rolls of Scotland''.</ref> It is assumed Sir Robert died shortly before this date.\n\n== Marriage and descendants ==\n\nRobert Lauder married sometime before 1489 Isabella Hay, daughter of [[John Hay, 1st Lord Hay of Yester]]. She was a descendant of [[Robert I of Scotland|Robert The Bruce]], and a great-great granddaughter of [[Robert III of Scotland|Robert III]].\n\nOf their children:\n* Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass (d. 1517/18).\n* William Lauder, from whom descend the [[Belhaven, Scotland|Belhaven]] and West Barns branch of this family<ref>Lawder, C.A.B.,''The Lawders of the Bass & their descendants'' (Belfast, 1914).</ref><ref>Fleming, D. Hay, and Beveridge, James, ''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1542\u20131548'', vol 3 (Edinburgh, 1936), no. 1063: 167</ref> including [[Sir Robert Lauder of Beilmouth]].\n* Agnes Lauder, married Alexander Cockburn of Newhall.<ref>Cockburn-Hood, Thomas H, ''House of Cockburn'' (Edinburgh, 1888), p. 264.</ref>\n* Elizabeth Lauder, married before October 1506, David Renton of Billie, & Lamberton.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), no.500: 227</ref>\n* Margaret, married (1) before September 1498, Kentigern Hepburn of Waughton and Lufness (d. July 1519),<ref>Hepburn, Edward, ''Genealogical Notes of the Hepburn Family'' (1925), 32.</ref> (2) 23 January 1521 (date of Papal Dispensation) Alexander Hume of [[Polwarth, Scottish Borders|Polwarth]], Berwickshire, who died May 1532 when she was still living.<ref>''The Humes of Polwarth'' (Edinburgh, 1894), pp. 179\u2013180</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n* ''Protocol Book of James Young'', [[Scottish Record Society]], Edinburgh, numbers 726, 1392, and 1468.\n* ''Exchequer Rolls: 1488\u20131496'', edited by George Burnett, vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1887),  , pps: 652, 679, 770\u20131, & 738.\n* ''Calendar of Documents relating to Scotland: 1357\u20131509'', edited by Joseph Bain, volume 4 (Edinburgh, 1888), number 1445.\n* ''The Grange of St.Giles'', by J.Stewart Smith, (Edinburgh, 1898).\n* ''Calendar of the Laing Charters, AD 854-1837'', edited by the Rev.John Anderson, (Edinburgh, 1899), numbers 64 (p.&nbsp;250), 196 (p.&nbsp;50), and p.&nbsp;153.\n* ''The Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529,'', vol. 1,  edited by M. Livingstone, (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1349, p.&nbsp;192.\n* ''The Berwick & East Lothian Coasts'', by Ian C. Hannah, (London, 1913), p.&nbsp;29).\n* ''Acts of the Lords of Council in Civil Causes, 1496 \u2013 1501'', volume II, page 261.\n* ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage'', edited by Peter Townend, 105th edition, (London, 1970), p.&nbsp;2687.\n* ''The Lauders of the Bass'', by G. M. S. Lauder-Frost, in ''East Lothian Life'', Autumn 1996, issue 22, {{ISSN|1361-7818}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauder, Robert, Of The Bass}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Category:1508 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish knights]]\n[[Category:People from East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Scottish soldiers]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 Parliament of Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegal transactions:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Lauder_of_the_Bass"}
{"title_page": "2014\u201315 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |mode             = Basketball\n  |year             = 2014\u201315\n  |prev_year        = 2013\u201314\n  |next_year        = 2015\u201316\n  |team             = Virginia Cavaliers\n  |image            = Virginia_Cavaliers_text_logo.svg\n  |image_size        = 180\n  |conference       = Atlantic Coast Conference\n  |division         = \n  |short_conf  = ACC\n  |CoachRank        = 8\n  |APRank           = 6\n  |record           = 30\u20134\n  |conf_record       = 16\u20132\n  |head_coach        = [[Tony Bennett (basketball, born 1969)|Tony Bennett]]\n  |hc_year           = 6th\n  |assoc_coach      = [[Ritchie McKay]] \n  |ahc_year         = 6th\n  |asst_coach1       = [[Ron Sanchez]]\n  |ac1_year         = 6th\n  |asst_coach2       = Jason Williford\n  |ac2_year         = 6th\n  |asst_coach3       = \n  |asst_coach4       = \n  |off_scheme          = [[Princeton offense|Princeton]], [[Motion offense|Motion]]\n  |def_scheme          = [[Glossary of basketball terms#P|Pack-line]]\n  |captain          = [[Malcolm Brogdon]]\n  |captain2         = [[Anthony Gill (basketball)|Anthony Gill]]\n  |captain3         = [[Darion Atkins]]\n  |stadium     =[[John Paul Jones Arena]]\n  |champion         = [[2014\u201315 Atlantic Coast Conference men's basketball season|ACC regular season]] champions<br>[[Barclays Center Classic]] champions\n  |tourney          = [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n  |tourney_result   =  Third Round\n}}\n{{2014\u201315 ACC men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''2014\u201315 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team''' represented the [[University of Virginia]] during the [[2014\u201315 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]], in their 110th season of play. The team was led by head coach Tony Bennett, in his sixth year, and played their home games at [[John Paul Jones Arena]] as members of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]].\n\nBuilding on the success of [[2013\u201314 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|the previous season]], the Cavaliers had their best regular season in program history with a record of 28\u20132, their first undefeated non-conference regular season record since [[2000\u201301 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|2000\u201301]], and their highest national ranking since [[1982\u201383 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|1982\u201383]], ranking at number two on the AP Poll for a total of seven weeks. The Cavaliers also became the first team outside of [[Tobacco Road rivalry|Tobacco Road]] to win back-to-back ACC regular season championships, with their conference record of 16\u20132. Particular highlights included holding Rutgers, Harvard, and Georgia Tech to under thirty points each. Virginia also held Harvard to a single field goal in the first half of their game, tying the NCAA record for fewest field goals allowed in the first half of a game since the [[shot clock]] was instituted in 1986.<ref name=\"harvard_record\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyprogress.com/cavalierinsider/no-virginia-hammers-harvard-in-historic-fashion/article_9f233f4a-8944-11e4-b194-8be8c6067517.html |title=No. 6 Virginia hammers Harvard in historic fashion |first=Whitey |last=Reid |work=[[The Daily Progress]] |date=22 December 2014 |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"harvard_espn\">{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/101636/the-most-impressive-part-of-uvas-49-point-win |title=Most impressive part of UVa's 49-point win |first=Eammonn |last=Brennan |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=22 December 2014 |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> However, late-season injuries, in particular [[Justin Anderson (basketball)|Justin Anderson's]] nearly five-week-long absence due to a broken finger and appendectomy, hurt the team, with the Cavaliers falling in a close loss to North Carolina in the [[2015 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]] semifinals. In the [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] they defeated Belmont in the second round before losing in the third round to Michigan State.\n\n==Last season==\nThe [[2013\u201314 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|Cavaliers]] finished the season 30\u20134 overall and 16\u20132 in conference play, finishing in first place in the ACC outright for the first time since [[1980\u201381 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|the 1980\u201381 season]]. They proceeded to win the [[2014 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]] for their second-ever conference championship. The team also tied for the most wins in a season in school history, set a school record for the most single-season conference wins, and earned their highest final national ranking since [[1981\u201382 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|1982]]. The Cavaliers received a #1 seed in the [[2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]], where they defeated [[2013\u201314 Coastal Carolina Chanticleers men's basketball team|Coastal Carolina]] and [[2013\u201314 Memphis Tigers men's basketball team|Memphis]] before losing to [[2013\u201314 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|Michigan State]] in the Sweet Sixteen.<ref name=\"lastseason\">{{cite web | title =  Curtain Falls on Extraordinary Basketball Season | url = http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032914aac.html | website= VirginiaSports.com - The University of Virginia Official Athletic Site | date = 29 March 2014 | accessdate = 8 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Departures===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n! Name !! Number !! Pos. !! Height !! Weight !! Year !! Hometown !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| Teven Jones || 5 || G || 6'0\" || 182 || Sophomore || [[Kannapolis, North Carolina|Kannapolis, NC]] || Transferred to [[Tarleton State Texans and TexAnns|Tarleton 