valiers|University of Virginia Sports]] |date=March 9, 2015 |accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and then followed on March 10 with individual awards from the [[United States Basketball Writers Association]].<ref name=\"USBWA_Awards\">{{Cite press release |url=http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031015aaa.html |title= Bennett, Brogdon and Anderson Earn USBWA District 3 Awards |publisher=[[Virginia Cavaliers|University of Virginia Sports]] |date=March 10, 2015 |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> On March 16, USBWA released All-American selections, naming Brogdon to their second team.<ref name=\"0316_AA\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/usbwa/news/2015/allamerica150316.html |title=USBWA NAMES 2014-15 ALL-AMERICANS |publisher=[[United States Basketball Writers Association]] |date=March 16, 2015 |accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref> One week later, USBWA named Bennett the [[Henry Iba Award]] winner.<ref name=\"iba_award\">{{cite press release |title=Virginia's Bennett Wins 2014-15 Henry Iba Coach of the Year Award |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/usbwa/news/2015/iba150323.html |publisher=[[United States Basketball Writers Association]] |date=March 23, 2015 |accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> On March 27, the [[National Association of Basketball Coaches]] released their District 2 awards.<ref name=\"nabc_d2_032715\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032715aaa.html |title=Bennett, Brogdon and Anderson Earn NABC District 2 Awards |publisher=University of Virginia Sports |date=March 27, 2015 |accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref> On March 30, the [[Associated Press]] and NABC named their All-American teams, including Brogdon on both organizations' second teams, and Anderson on the NABC third team.<ref name=\"nabc_aa_033015\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/033015aaa.html |title= Brogdon and Anderson Named NABC All-Americans |publisher=University of Virginia Sports |date=March 30, 2015 |accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ap_aa_033015\">{{cite news |url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/03/30/the-ap-released-their-all-american-teams-on-monday/ |title=The AP released their All-American teams on Monday |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |date=March 30, 2015 |accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Tony Bennett (basketball, born 1969)|Tony Bennett]]\n** [[Atlantic Coast Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year]] (ACSMA, ACC Coaches)\n** USBWA District 3 Coach of the Year\n** [[Henry Iba Award]]\n** NABC District 2 Coach of the Year\n* [[Justin Anderson (basketball)|Justin Anderson]]\n** All-ACC Second Team (ACSMA, ACC Coaches)\n** USBWA All-District 3 Team\n** NABC All-District 2 First Team\n** [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] [[2015 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|Third-Team All-American]]\n* Darion Atkins\n** ACC Defensive Player of the Year (ACSMA)\n** ACC All-Defensive Team (ACSMA)\n** [[Lefty Driesell Award]]\n* [[Malcolm Brogdon]]\n** ACC Co-Defensive Player of the Year (ACC Coaches)\n** All-ACC First Team (ACSMA, ACC Coaches)\n** ACC All-Defensive Team (ACSMA, ACC Coaches)\n** USBWA All-District 3 Team\n** All-[[2015 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]] Second Team\n** USBWA [[2015 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|Second Team All-American]]\n** NABC All-District 2 First Team\n** NABC Second Team All-American\n** [[Associated Press]] Second Team All-American\n* Anthony Gill\n** All-ACC Third Team (ACSMA)\n** ACC All-Defensive Team (ACC Coaches)\n* London Perrantes\n** All-ACC Honorable Mention (ACSMA)\n* Mike Tobey\n** ACC [[Sixth man|Sixth Man]] of the Year (ACC Coaches)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014-15 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team}}\n[[Category:Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball seasons]]\n[[Category:2014\u201315 Atlantic Coast Conference men's basketball season|Virginia]]\n[[Category:2014 in sports in Virginia|Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball]]\n[[Category:2015 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament participants|Virginia]]\n[[Category:2015 in sports in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |mode             = Basketball\n  |year             = 2014\u201315\n  |prev_year        = 2013\u201314\n  |next_year        = 2015\u201316\n  |team             = Virginia Cavaliers\n  |image            = Virginia_Cavaliers_text_logo.svg\n  |image_size        = 180\n  |conference       = Atlantic Coast Conference\n  |division         = \n  |short_conf  = ACC\n  |CoachRank        = 8\n  |APRank           = 6\n  |record           = 30\u20134\n  |conf_record       = 16\u20132\n  |head_coach        = [[Tony Bennett (basketball, born 1969)|Tony Bennett]]\n  |hc_year           = 6th\n  |assoc_coach      = [[Ritchie McKay]] \n  |ahc_year         = 6th\n  |asst_coach1       = [[Ron Sanchez]]\n  |ac1_year         = 6th\n  |asst_coach2       = Jason Williford\n  |ac2_year         = 6th\n  |asst_coach3       = \n  |asst_coach4       = \n  |off_scheme          = [[Princeton offense|Princeton]], [[Motion offense|Motion]]\n  |def_scheme          = [[Glossary of basketball terms#P|Pack-line]]\n  |captain          = [[Malcolm Brogdon]]\n  |captain2         = [[Anthony Gill (basketball)|Anthony Gill]]\n  |captain3         = [[Darion Atkins]]\n  |stadium     =[[John Paul Jones Arena]]\n  |champion         = [[2014\u201315 Atlantic Coast Conference men's basketball season|ACC regular season]] champions<br>[[Barclays Center Classic]] champions\n  |tourney          = [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n  |tourney_result   =  Third Round\n}}\n{{2014\u201315 ACC men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''2014\u201315 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team''' represented the [[University of Virginia]] during the [[2014\u201315 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]], in their 110th season of play. The team was led by head coach Tony Bennett, in his sixth year, and played their home games at [[John Paul Jones Arena]] as members of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]].\n\nBuilding on the success of [[2013\u201314 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|the previous season]], the Cavaliers had their best regular season in program history with a record of 28\u20132, their first undefeated non-conference regular season record since [[2000\u201301 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|2000\u201301]], and their highest national ranking since [[1982\u201383 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|1982\u201383]], ranking at number two on the AP Poll for a total of seven weeks. The Cavaliers also became the first team outside of [[Tobacco Road rivalry|Tobacco Road]] to win back-to-back ACC regular season championships, with their conference record of 16\u20132. Particular highlights included holding Rutgers, Harvard, and Georgia Tech to under thirty points each. Virginia also held Harvard to a single field goal in the first half of their game, tying the NCAA record for fewest field goals allowed in the first half of a game since the [[shot clock]] was instituted in 1986.<ref name=\"harvard_record\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyprogress.com/cavalierinsider/no-virginia-hammers-harvard-in-historic-fashion/article_9f233f4a-8944-11e4-b194-8be8c6067517.html |title=No. 6 Virginia hammers Harvard in historic fashion |first=Whitey |last=Reid |work=[[The Daily Progress]] |date=22 December 2014 |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"harvard_espn\">{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/101636/the-most-impressive-part-of-uvas-49-point-win |title=Most impressive part of UVa's 49-point win |first=Eammonn |last=Brennan |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=22 December 2014 |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> However, late-season injuries, in particular [[Justin Anderson (basketball)|Justin Anderson's]] nearly five-week-long absence due to a broken finger and appendectomy, hurt the team, with the Cavaliers falling in a close loss to North Carolina in the [[2015 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]] semifinals. In the [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] they defeated Belmont in the second round before losing in the third round to Michigan State.\n\n==Last season==\nThe [[2013\u201314 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|Cavaliers]] finished the season 30\u20134 overall and 16\u20132 in conference play, finishing in first place in the ACC outright for the first time since [[1980\u201381 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|the 1980\u201381 season]]. They proceeded to win the [[2014 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC Tournament]] for their second-ever conference championship. The team also tied for the most wins in a season in school history, set a school record for the most single-season conference wins, and earned their highest final national ranking since [[1981\u201382 Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball team|1982]]. The Cavaliers received a #1 seed in the [[2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]], where they defeated [[2013\u201314 Coastal Carolina Chanticleers men's basketball team|Coastal Carolina]] and [[2013\u201314 Memphis Tigers men's basketball team|Memphis]] before losing to [[2013\u201314 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|Michigan State]] in the Sweet Sixteen.<ref name=\"lastseason\">{{cite web | title =  Curtain Falls on Extraordinary Basketball Season | url = http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032914aac.html | website= VirginiaSports.com - The University of Virginia Official Athletic Site | date = 29 March 2014 | accessdate = 8 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Departures===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n! Name !! Number !! Pos. !! Height !! Weight !! Year !! Hometown !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| Teven Jones || 5 || G