"label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_rowing_(UK)"}
{"title_page": "Bushey", "text_new": "{{about||other similar names|Bushi (disambiguation)|and|Bushy (disambiguation)}}\n{{redirect|Bushey Park|the park in Richmond upon Thames|Bushy Park||Bushy Park (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n\n{{infobox UK place\n|country =           England\n|official_name=      Bushey\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.6429|-0.3604|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name = The High Street, Bushey - geograph.org.uk - 84349.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Bushey High Street in 2005\n|population =        25,763\n|shire_district=     [[Hertsmere]]\n|shire_county =      [[Hertfordshire]]\n|region =            East of England\n|post_town=          BUSHEY\n|postcode_district=  WD23\n|postcode_area=      WD\n|dial_code=          01923\n|os_grid_reference=  TQ132952\n|constituency_westminster= [[Hertsmere (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertsmere]]\n}}\n'''Bushey''' is a town in the [[Hertsmere]] borough of [[Hertfordshire]] in the [[East of England]]. It has a population of 24,000. '''Bushey Heath''' is a large neighbourhood south east of Bushey on the boundary with the [[London Borough of Harrow]] reaching elevations of {{convert|165|m}} above sea level.<ref>OS Explorer Map 173, 2010 edition</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first written record of Bushey is an account in the [[Domesday Book]], which describes a small agricultural village named 'Bissei' (which later became 'Biss(h)e' and then 'Bisheye' during the 12th century). However, chance archaeological findings of [[Stone Age]] tools provide evidence that the area was inhabited as far back as the [[Palaeolithic]] period. The town also has links to the [[Roman Britain|Roman]] occupation of [[Great Britain|Britain]], with the main road running through it being Roman; sites of possible Roman villas being unearthed in the area; and a Roman tessellated pavement was discovered near Chiltern Avenue.<ref>{{PastScape|mnumber=398249 |mname=|accessdate= 27 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Saint James Church.jpg|thumb|left|[[James, son of Zebedee|St. James]]'s Church, Bushey]]\nThe origin of the town's name is not fully known. In terms of the original name, \"Bissei,\" an early theory in Reverend J.B. Johnstone's book ''The Place-Names of England and Wales'' states that it may have meant \"Byssa's Isle,\" and it started life as a lake-village surrounded by marshes, streams and lakes.  A more modern theory (but less romantic) is that it is simply derived from the Old English word ''bysce'' and Old French ''boisseie'', meaning a 'place covered with wood'. The latter theory could prove more apt, as the town is located in the valleys which extend southwards from the [[Chiltern Hills]], which were once covered in dense forests of [[oak]], [[elm]], [[Fraxinus|ash]], [[hazel]] and [[juniper]].\n\nBushey Heath's story begins in the [[Napoleonic Wars]] during a large food shortage. To help solve the problem, the government awarded the waste land to the east of Bushey to Bushey landowners to be used as farming; the land was more generally known as Bushey Common. Whilst the original aim was to produce food, being close to a railway and up to 500&nbsp;ft above sea level with beautiful and broad views made the area attractive for housing developers.\n\nThe 19th and 20th centuries marked the time of most change in Bushey, especially between 1860 and 1960. The population rose 28-fold within 200 years, from 856 in 1801, to just under 24,000 today. The expansion was for many reasons, one of the main ones being due to the boom in industry caused by the railway in the early 20th century. A result was that many new jobs were created in and around [[Watford]], and in the early 1920s, Bushey's first council houses were built. More housing was later built for the service families working in defence organisations in [[Stanmore]] and [[Northwood, London|Northwood]]. The expansion eventually died down because much of the land in and around Bushey was protected under the [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] after the [[Second World War]].\n\nThis same Green Belt legislation was also partly responsible for the abandonment of the pre-war [[Edgware tube station|Edgware]] to [[Bushey Heath tube station|Bushey Heath]] extension as part of the [[Northern line#The Northern Heights plan|Northern Heights]] programme of the [[Northern line]] underground railway. The [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] put great restrictions on new development, and the plan was to use the new railway to stimulate new housing around the new route; without the new housing the route was deemed no longer viable. However, as work was advanced at the onset of war, the depot was completed for use as bomber manufacture, and following the Second World War and Green Belt coming into force, it was converted into the [[Aldenham]] bus depot (of [[Cliff Richard]]'s ''[[Summer Holiday (1963 film)|Summer Holiday]]'' fame), which it remained until 1985, when it became derelict. It was redeveloped in 1996 and is now the Centennial Park Industrial Estate ({{coord|51.639954|-0.308561|source:google|display=inline}}). [[Bushey Heath tube station|Bushey Heath station]] would have been located at the intersection of Elstree Road and [[A41 road|Northwestern Avenue]] ({{coord|51.64245|-0.3200|source:Google|display=inline}}). Conceptual plans existed in the 1903 [[Act of Parliament]] for an [[Edgware]] to [[Watford]] railway that would have seen the railway extended at a later date though Bushey village and on to Watford market, but even less came of that than the partially completed [[Edgware tube station|Edgware]] to [[Bushey Heath tube station|Bushey Heath]] stretch.\n\nThe highest point in the historic county of [[Middlesex]] was in Bushey Heath on the border between Hertfordshire and Middlesex at the junction of the A4140 and the A409. At 153&nbsp;m (502&nbsp;ft) above sea level, the grid reference was TQ 152937.\n\n===Stories, legends and folklore===\nThe lack of farming in Bushey Heath meant that it was a heavily wooded area up to the 18th century, and this, added to the lack of street lighting and police, meant that Bushey Heath's history is full of tales of thieves, highwaymen and even murder. According to Grant Longman's ''Robberies on Bushey Heath'', the road from Bushey Heath to [[Stanmore]] is said to be where the highwaymen lurked, ready to raid the dozen or so caravans that passed through Bushey Heath daily, carrying money from trade in London. Before venturing through the pass, parties of travellers and merchants would form at the ''Boot Inn'' at [[Edgware]] and the ''Three Crowns'' at Bushey Heath so they did not have to venture through the pass alone. Although one of the highwaymen responsible for the attacks is rumoured to have been the notorious [[Dick Turpin]], evidence suggests that he was in fact more active in the region of [[Essex]].\n\n==Local government==\n\nBushey was an ancient [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]]. It was subdivided by the [[Local Government Act 1894]] into two: the part which was within the [[Watford]] urban district became the 'Bushey Urban' parish, in the [[Watford Rural District]], and the part which was outside became 'Bushey Rural' parish. Subsequently, in 1906, the Bushey Urban parish was renamed [[Oxhey]], and the Bushey Rural parish became the parish of Bushey in the Bushey Urban District.\n\n==Modern day==\n[[Image:Bushey High Street 2.jpg|thumb|High Street, Bushey]]\n\nDespite being close to London and having Watford on its doorstep Bushey retains the feeling of a small town and this is reinforced with events such as the [[Bushey Festival]] and quarter marathon which is held each July and the Horticultural Society's flower and produce show.\n\nBeing located near several film [[Elstree Studios|studios at Elstree and Borehamwood]], Bushey and Bushey Heath frequently feature as backdrops for many film and TV shows. Most notable is a bus scene in the ''[[Cannon and Ball]]'' film, and in the 1957 film ''[[Lucky Jim]]''. Several historic buildings in Bushey, notably the old [[Royal Masonic School for Boys]], later the International University, in the Avenue, have been used in films over a long period of time, including, ''[[Nuns on the Run]]'', ''[[Out of Bounds (2003 film)|Out of Bounds]]'', ''[[Children of Men]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter]]''. and also the comedy series ''[[Little Britain]]''. It has also been the set for several television series, including ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' and ''[[Little Britain]]''. This site is currently being redeveloped for residential usage, with the 1960s additions to the site having been demolished.\n\nMany of ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' episodes include location shots around the Bushey area, and the latter half of the ''[[Confessions of a Driving Instructor]]'' is entirely shot on the roads between Elstree and Bushey, finishing in the car dump at 'Bushey Breakers'.\n\nThe [[University of London]], located in the Bushey area has been used in the filming of BBC's [[Grange Hill]] and also for various other programmes, such as [[family business]]. Pupils from local schools including [[Bushey Hall School|Bushey Hall]] and [[Bushey Meads School|Bushey Meads]] have taken part as extras in productions such as ''[[My Dad's the Prime Minister]]''.\n\nBushey Heath is home to a duck pond, (Warren Lake) which was restored in 1992 after falling into dereliction.\n\n==Schools==\nThe area contains a mix of primary schools and linked infants and junior schools (see [[Primary schools in Hertsmere#Bushey|schools in Bushey]]).\n\nThe state secondary schools are [[Queens' School, Hertfordshire|Queens' School]], [[Bushey Meads School]] and [[Bushey Academy]] (also known as Bushey Hall), of which the first two generally do well in comparison with other schools in the county. Bushey is also the site of the famous [[Purcell School]], a school for young musicians well known for turning out many successful musicians. It was formerly the [[Royal Caledonian School]]. There are also two private girls' schools, St. Hilda's and [[St Margaret's School, Bushey|St Margaret's]] in the area.\n\n==Herkomer's Art School==\n\nHubert Herkomer was a poor immigrant from [[Bavaria]], who moved to Bushey in 1874, and ended life in 1914 as [[Hubert von Herkomer|Sir Hubert von Herkomer]] [[Royal Academy|RA]] [[Royal Victorian Order|CVO]]. Herkomer had visited a friend who lived in Bushey in 1873, and returned to rent a pair of cottages and a studio near Melbourne Road. He founded Herkomer's Art School at Bushey in 1883, which, in its 21-year life, attracted some 500 students to the area, some of whom stayed after establishing their own studios. Their paintings are on display in the [[Bushey Museum]]. A street, Herkomer Road, was named in his memory.\n\nAt around 1888, he built [[Lululaund]] ({{coord|51.643908|-0.36065|display=inline}}), a 'Bavarian castle', which was named after his second wife Lulu Griffiths. After being married for only a year she died. Lululaund dominated the Bushey skyline until 1939 when it was almost entirely demolished; a lot of the building was used as hardcore for [[RAF Bovingdon|Bovingdon Airfield]], and much of the woodwork and carvings from the castle were burnt.\n\nIn 2014 the surviving remnant of Lululaund was converted into luxury apartments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/latestupdates.jsp |title=Bushey Rose Garden, Latest News |publisher=Hertsmere Council |accessdate=15 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418164353/http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/latestupdates.jsp |archivedate=18 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/history.jsp |title=The History of the Rose Garden |publisher=Hertsmere Council |accessdate=15 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422000804/http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/history.jsp |archivedate=22 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSir Hubert is mainly remembered as an artist today, but in his time he was a polymath, becoming involved in some of the earliest film productions in Europe, and starting a series of races and time trials for cars in Germany.\n\nIn 1904 Herkomer closed his school and sold the building. The school was re-opened in 1905 on the same site by the artist [[Lucy Kemp-Welch]] as the Bushey School of Painting. In 1912 Herkomer bought back the school building and demolished it. A [[Bushey Rose Garden|rose garden]] was laid out on the site to a design by [[T.H. Mawson]].<ref name=rose>{{cite web|title=Bushey Rose Garden|url=http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/Parks--Leisure/Parks--Open-Spaces/Bushey-Rose-Garden/History-and-Restoration.aspx|website=Parks and Leisure|publisher=Hertsmere Borough Council|accessdate=24 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140824070036/http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/Parks--Leisure/Parks--Open-Spaces/Bushey-Rose-Garden/History-and-Restoration.aspx|archivedate=24 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is listed grade II on the [[Register of Parks and Gardens]].<ref name=\"HE\">{{NHLE |num=1001649 |desc=Rose Garden, Bushey |accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere is a gallery named after Kemp-Welch close to the village church. It is more usually used as a village hall today, with occasional exhibitions such as one in September 2006 by students from the [[Chelsea College of Art]].\n\n==Bushey Miniature Railway==\nBushey Miniature Railway is a fairly recent addition to Bushey village. Work started in September 2017 and the railway continues to grow. The railway is 5 inch (so big enough to take adults and children) and 90 meters long. The railway runs a battery electric locomotive and various passenger carriages and is located in the large garden of an old Georgian house in the high street. The Bushey Miniature Railway is a private railway at the moment, with plans to operate for visitors on open days in the Spring and Summer.\n\n==Film studios==\n{{Main|Bushey Studios}}\nBushey Film Studios in Melbourne Road were originally built by Hubert Herkomer and operated between 1913 and 1985. For much of its existence the studios focused on low-budget productions.\n\n==Jewish cemeteries==\nThere are two [[Jewish cemetery|Jewish cemeteries]], serving a sector of north-west London. Bushey 'Old' Cemetery is at Little Bushey Lane and Bushey 'New' Cemetery is {{convert|600|m}} along the same road. Both are active for funerals, stone-settings and visiting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/bushey-cemetery|title=Bushey Cemetery &#124; United Synagogue|website=www.theus.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 a \u00a36.12 m extension was built, as the 43,000 grave spaces in the old cemetery were nearly full, and another 17,000 were thought necessary to provide for the next 50 years. {{convert|16|acre}} of new land were laid out by the landscape architects J and L Gibbons, with two prayer halls, offices and a mortuary. There are also separate rooms for the [[Cohanim]], who are not permitted to be in the same space as the coffin, but may view proceedings through glass walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2018/jan/07/bushey-jewish-cemetery-extension-review|title=Bushey Jewish Cemetery review \u2013 a place of dignity and ease|first=Rowan|last=Moore|date=7 January 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- *** Please remember to add the Category:People from Bushey to the page of anybody you add to this list *** -->\n{{div col |colwidth=30em}}\n*[[George Michael]], musician, [[Wham!]], attended Bushey Meads School\n*[[Andrew Ridgeley]], musician, [[Wham!]], attended Bushey Meads School\n*[[R. D. Blackmore]], novelist, lived briefly in Bushey\n*[[Freddie Bunce]], footballer\n*[[Dave Cash (disc jockey)|Dave Cash]], disc jockey, born in Bushey\n*[[Helen Cherry]], actor, born in Bushey\n*[[Peter Copley]], actor, born in Bushey\n*[[Oliver Dowden]], Member of Parliament for Hertsmere\n*[[John Gale (poker player)|John Gale]], poker player\n*[[Divina Galica]], skier and racing driver, born in Bushey Heath\n*[[Phil Gillies]], Canadian politician, born in Bushey\n*[[Hubert von Herkomer]], artist, owner of [[Lululaund]]\n*[[Shirlie Holliman]], musician, of [[Pepsi & Shirlie]], attended [[Bushey Meads School]]\n*[[Tom Howard (special effects)|Tom Howard]], Oscar-winning film special effects man, lived in Bushey from 1946 until his death in 1985\n*[[Lucy Kemp-Welch]], artist\n*[[Bill Kerr]], actor and radio broadcaster lived in the high street. He starred as Flight Lieutenant H. B. \"Micky\" Martin, pilot of \"Popsie\" in the ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|Dam Busters]]''\n*[[Simon Le Bon]], musician, [[Duran Duran]], born in Bushey\n*[[A. E. Matthews]], character actor, lived in Bushey until his death. He has a blue plaque in Little Bushey Lane.\n*Dr [[Thomas Monro (art collector)|Thomas Monro]], Principal Physician of [[Bethlem Hospital|Bedlam]] and who attended on [[King George III]] in his last illness, settled his family here in the 19th century\n*[[Tony O'Malley (musician)|Tony O'Malley]], musician, born in Bushey\n*[[Josef Perl]], Holocaust survivor, lives in Bushey\n*[[Sid Phillips (musician)|Sid Phillips]], musician, band leader, lived in Bushey Heath\n*[[Simon Phillips (drummer)|Simon Phillips]], musician, drummer [[Toto (band)|Toto]], lived in Bushey Heath\n*[[Roy Plomley]], radio presenter, created [[Desert Island Discs]] whilst living in a cottage at Little Bushey Lane\n*[[Michael Portillo]], journalist, broadcaster and former politician, born in Bushey\n*[[Mark Ramprakash]], cricketer, born in Bushey\n*[[William Hurst Rees]], surveyor\n*[[Mich\u00e8le Roberts]], writer\n*[[Gilbert Taylor]], cinematographer, born in Bushey Heath\n*[[Henry Wylde]], conductor and musician\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Twin town==\nBushey has been twinned with German town [[Landsberg am Lech]] in Bavaria ([[Southern Germany]]) for its historical link. To Landsberg belonged the native village, Waal, of artist ''Herkomer'' detailed above. The towns retain links for mayoral duties and school exchange trips.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bushey Hall]]\n*[[Bushey Hall Golf Club]]\n*[[Bushey Museum]]\n*[[Bushey railway station]]\n*[[RAF Bushey Hall]]\n\n==Nearest places==\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring areas'''\n|Northwest = [[Watford]]\n|North     = [[Aldenham]]\n|Northeast = [[Aldenham|Patchetts Green]] and [[Letchmore Heath]]\n|West      = [[Oxhey]]\n|Centre    = Bushey\n|East      = [[Aldenham|Aldenham Park]] [[Elstree|Elstree Aerodrome, Hilfield Park Reservoir, Aldenham Reservoir and Elstree]]\n|Southwest = Merry Hill, 76 ha. woodland managed by the Woodland Trust, Haydon Hill then [[Carpenders Park]]\n|South     =  [[Headstone, London|Headstone]]<br>[[Harrow Weald]] <br />\n(across Hartsbourne Golf & Country Club; [[Grim's Ditch (Harrow)|Grim's Ditch]]; [[Harrow Weald Common]])\n|Southeast = [[Stanmore Common]] and [[Bentley Priory]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{cite book|last=Youngs|first=FA|title=Guide to the Local Administrative Units of England|publisher=Royal Historical Society|location=London|origyear=1981|year=1991|volume=1 (of 2)}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43267 |title=Parishes: Bushey |editor=William Page |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |date=1908 |work=A History of the County of Hertford: volume 2 |accessdate=28 April 2014 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Hertfordshire}}\n{{Civil parishes of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Hertsmere]]\n[[Category:Highest points of English counties]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||other similar names|Bushi (disambiguation)|and|Bushy (disambiguation)}}\n{{redirect|Bushey Park|the park in Richmond upon Thames|Bushy Park||Bushy Park (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n\n{{infobox UK place\n|country =           England\n|official_name=      Bushey\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.6429|-0.3604|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name = The High Street, Bushey - geograph.org.uk - 84349.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Bushey High Street in 2005\n|population =        25,763\n|shire_district=     [[Hertsmere]]\n|shire_county =      [[Hertfordshire]]\n|region =            East of England\n|post_town=          BUSHEY\n|postcode_district=  WD23\n|postcode_area=      WD\n|dial_code=          01923\n|os_grid_reference=  TQ132952\n|constituency_westminster= [[Hertsmere (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertsmere]]\n}}\n'''Bushey''' is a town in the [[Hertsmere]] borough of [[Hertfordshire]] in the [[East of England]]. It has a population of 24,000. '''Bushey Heath''' is a large neighbourhood south east of Bushey on the boundary with the [[London Borough of Harrow]] reaching elevations of {{convert|165|m}} above sea level.<ref>OS Explorer Map 173, 2010 edition</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first written record of Bushey is an account in the [[Domesday Book]], which describes a small agricultural village named 'Bissei' (which later became 'Biss(h)e' and then 'Bisheye' during the 12th century). However, chance archaeological findings of [[Stone Age]] tools provide evidence that the area was inhabited as far back as the [[Palaeolithic]] period. The town also has links to the [[Roman Britain|Roman]] occupation of [[Great Britain|Britain]], with the main road running through it being Roman; sites of possible Roman villas being unearthed in the area; and a Roman tessellated pavement was discovered near Chiltern Avenue.<ref>{{PastScape|mnumber=398249 |mname=|accessdate= 27 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Saint James Church.jpg|thumb|left|[[James, son of Zebedee|St. James]]'s Church, Bushey]]\nThe origin of the town's name is not fully known. In terms of the original name, \"Bissei,\" an early theory in Reverend J.B. Johnstone's book ''The Place-Names of England and Wales'' states that it may have meant \"Byssa's Isle,\" and it started life as a lake-village surrounded by marshes, streams and lakes.  A more modern theory (but less romantic) is that it is simply derived from the Old English word ''bysce'' and Old French ''boisseie'', meaning a 'place covered with wood'. The latter theory could prove more apt, as the town is located in the valleys which extend southwards from the [[Chiltern Hills]], which were once covered in dense forests of [[oak]], [[elm]], [[Fraxinus|ash]], [[hazel]] and [[juniper]].\n\nBushey Heath's story begins in the [[Napoleonic Wars]] during a large food shortage. To help solve the problem, the government awarded the waste land to the east of Bushey to Bushey landowners to be used as farming; the land was more generally known as Bushey Common. Whilst the original aim was to produce food, being close to a railway and up to 500&nbsp;ft above sea level with beautiful and broad views made the area attractive for housing developers.\n\nThe 19th and 20th centuries marked the time of most change in Bushey, especially between 1860 and 1960. The population rose 28-fold within 200 years, from 856 in 1801, to just under 24,000 today. The expansion was for many reasons, one of the main ones being due to the boom in industry caused by the railway in the early 20th century. A result was that many new jobs were created in and around [[Watford]], and in the early 1920s, Bushey's first council houses were built. More housing was later built for the service families working in defence organisations in [[Stanmore]] and [[Northwood, London|Northwood]]. The expansion eventually died down because much of the land in and around Bushey was protected under the [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] after the [[Second World War]].\n\nThis same Green Belt legislation was also partly responsible for the abandonment of the pre-war [[Edgware tube station|Edgware]] to [[Bushey Heath tube station|Bushey Heath]] extension as part of the [[Northern line#The Northern Heights plan|Northern Heights]] programme of the [[Northern line]] underground railway. The [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] put great restrictions on new development, and the plan was to use the new railway to stimulate new housing around the new route; without the new housing the route was deemed no longer viable. However, as work was advanced at the onset of war, the depot was completed for use as bomber manufacture, and following the Second World War and Green Belt coming into force, it was converted into the [[Aldenham]] bus depot (of [[Cliff Richard]]'s ''[[Summer Holiday (1963 film)|Summer Holiday]]'' fame), which it remained until 1985, when it became derelict. It was redeveloped in 1996 and is now the Centennial Park Industrial Estate ({{coord|51.639954|-0.308561|source:google|display=inline}}). [[Bushey Heath tube station|Bushey Heath station]] would have been located at the intersection of Elstree Road and [[A41 road|Northwestern Avenue]] ({{coord|51.64245|-0.3200|source:Google|display=inline}}). Conceptual plans existed in the 1903 [[Act of Parliament]] for an [[Edgware]] to [[Watford]] railway that would have seen the railway extended at a later date though Bushey village and on to Watford market, but even less came of that than the partially completed [[Edgware tube station|Edgware]] to [[Bushey Heath tube station|Bushey Heath]] stretch.\n\nThe highest point in the historic county of [[Middlesex]] was in Bushey Heath on the border between Hertfordshire and Middlesex at the junction of the A4140 and the A409. At 153&nbsp;m (502&nbsp;ft) above sea level, the grid reference was TQ 152937.\n\n===Stories, legends and folklore===\nThe lack of farming in Bushey Heath meant that it was a heavily wooded area up to the 18th century, and this, added to the lack of street lighting and police, meant that Bushey Heath's history is full of tales of thieves, highwaymen and even murder. According to Grant Longman's ''Robberies on Bushey Heath'', the road from Bushey Heath to [[Stanmore]] is said to be where the highwaymen lurked, ready to raid the dozen or so caravans that passed through Bushey Heath daily, carrying money from trade in London. Before venturing through the pass, parties of travellers and merchants would form at the ''Boot Inn'' at [[Edgware]] and the ''Three Crowns'' at Bushey Heath so they did not have to venture through the pass alone. Although one of the highwaymen responsible for the attacks is rumoured to have been the notorious [[Dick Turpin]], evidence suggests that he was in fact more active in the region of [[Essex]].\n\n==Local government==\n\nBushey was an ancient [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]]. It was subdivided by the [[Local Government Act 1894]] into two: the part which was within the [[Watford]] urban district became the 'Bushey Urban' parish, in the [[Watford Rural District]], and the part which was outside became 'Bushey Rural' parish. Subsequently, in 1906, the Bushey Urban parish was renamed [[Oxhey]], and the Bushey Rural parish became the parish of Bushey in the Bushey Urban District.\n\n==Modern day==\n[[Image:Bushey High Street 2.jpg|thumb|High Street, Bushey]]\n\nDespite being close to London and having Watford on its doorstep Bushey retains the feeling of a small town and this is reinforced with events such as the [[Bushey Festival]] and quarter marathon which is held each July and the Horticultural Society's flower and produce show.\n\nBeing located near several film [[Elstree Studios|studios at Elstree and Borehamwood]], Bushey and Bushey Heath frequently feature as backdrops for many film and TV shows. Most notable is a bus scene in the ''[[Cannon and Ball]]'' film, and in the 1957 film ''[[Lucky Jim]]''. Several historic buildings in Bushey, notably the old [[Royal Masonic School for Boys]], later the International University, in the Avenue, have been used in films over a long period of time, including, ''[[Nuns on the Run]]'', ''[[Out of Bounds (2003 film)|Out of Bounds]]'', ''[[Children of Men]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter]]''. and also the comedy series ''[[Little Britain]]''. It has also been the set for several television series, including ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' and ''[[Little Britain]]''. This site is currently being redeveloped for residential usage, with the 1960s additions to the site having been demolished.\n\nMany of ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' episodes include location shots around the Bushey area, and the latter half of the ''[[Confessions of a Driving Instructor]]'' is entirely shot on the roads between Elstree and Bushey, finishing in the car dump at 'Bushey Breakers'.\n\nThe [[University of London]], located in the Bushey area has been used in the filming of BBC's [[Grange Hill]] and also for various other programmes, such as [[family business]]. Pupils from local schools including [[Bushey Hall School|Bushey Hall]] and [[Bushey Meads School|Bushey Meads]] have taken part as extras in productions such as ''[[My Dad's the Prime Minister]]''.\n\nBushey Heath is home to a duck pond, (Warren Lake) which was restored in 1992 after falling into dereliction.\n\n==Schools==\nThe area contains a mix of primary schools and linked infants and junior schools (see [[Primary schools in Hertsmere#Bushey|schools in Bushey]]).\n\nThe state secondary schools are [[Queens' School, Hertfordshire|Queens' School]], [[Bushey Meads School]] and [[Bushey Academy]] (also known as Bushey Hall), of which the first two generally do well in comparison with other schools in the county. Bushey is also the site of the famous [[Purcell School]], a school for young musicians well known for turning out many successful musicians. It was formerly the [[Royal Caledonian School]]. There are also two private girls' schools, St. Hilda's and [[St Margaret's School, Bushey|St Margaret's]] in the area.\n\n==Herkomer's Art School==\n\nHubert Herkomer was a poor immigrant from [[Bavaria]], who moved to Bushey in 1874, and ended life in 1914 as [[Hubert von Herkomer|Sir Hubert von Herkomer]] [[Royal Academy|RA]] [[Royal Victorian Order|CVO]]. Herkomer had visited a friend who lived in Bushey in 1873, and returned to rent a pair of cottages and a studio near Melbourne Road. He founded Herkomer's Art School at Bushey in 1883, which, in its 21-year life, attracted some 500 students to the area, some of whom stayed after establishing their own studios. Their paintings are on display in the [[Bushey Museum]]. A street, Herkomer Road, was named in his memory.\n\nAt around 1888, he built [[Lululaund]] ({{coord|51.643908|-0.36065|display=inline}}), a 'Bavarian castle', which was named after his second wife Lulu Griffiths. After being married for only a year she died. Lululaund dominated the Bushey skyline until 1939 when it was almost entirely demolished; a lot of the building was used as hardcore for [[RAF Bovingdon|Bovingdon Airfield]], and much of the woodwork and carvings from the castle were burnt.\n\nIn 2014 the surviving remnant of Lululaund was converted into luxury apartments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/latestupdates.jsp |title=Bushey Rose Garden, Latest News |publisher=Hertsmere Council |accessdate=15 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418164353/http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/latestupdates.jsp |archivedate=18 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/history.jsp |title=The History of the Rose Garden |publisher=Hertsmere Council |accessdate=15 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422000804/http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/environmentplanning/parksandopenspaces/busheyrosegarden_3/history.jsp |archivedate=22 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSir Hubert is mainly remembered as an artist today, but in his time he was a polymath, becoming involved in some of the earliest film productions in Europe, and starting a series of races and time trials for cars in Germany.\n\nIn 1904 Herkomer closed his school and sold the building. The school was re-opened in 1905 on the same site by the artist [[Lucy Kemp-Welch]] as the Bushey School of Painting. In 1912 Herkomer bought back the school building and demolished it. A [[Bushey Rose Garden|rose garden]] was laid out on the site to a design by [[T.H. Mawson]].<ref name=rose>{{cite web|title=Bushey Rose Garden|url=http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/Parks--Leisure/Parks--Open-Spaces/Bushey-Rose-Garden/History-and-Restoration.aspx|website=Parks and Leisure|publisher=Hertsmere Borough Council|accessdate=24 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140824070036/http://www.hertsmere.gov.uk/Parks--Leisure/Parks--Open-Spaces/Bushey-Rose-Garden/History-and-Restoration.aspx|archivedate=24 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is listed grade II on the [[Register of Parks and Gardens]].<ref name=\"HE\">{{NHLE |num=1001649 |desc=Rose Garden, Bushey |accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere is a gallery named after Kemp-Welch close to the village church. It is more usually used as a village hall today, with occasional exhibitions such as one in September 2006 by students from the [[Chelsea College of Art]].\n\n==Bushey Miniature Railway==\nBushey Miniature Railway is a fairly recent addition to Bushey village. Work started in September 2017 and the railway continues to grow. The railway is 5 inch (so big enough to take adults and children) and 90 meters long. The railway runs a battery electric locomotive and various passenger carriages and is located in the large garden of an old Georgian house in the high street. The Bushey Miniature Railway is a private railway at the moment, with plans to operate for visitors on open days in the Spring and Summer.\n\n==Film studios==\n{{Main|Bushey Studios}}\nBushey Film Studios in Melbourne Road were originally built by Hubert Herkomer and operated between 1913 and 1985. For much of its existence the studios focused on low-budget productions.\n\n==Jewish cemeteries==\nThere are two [[Jewish cemetery|Jewish cemeteries]], serving a sector of north-west London. Bushey 'Old' Cemetery is at Little Bushey Lane and Bushey 'New' Cemetery is {{convert|600|m}} along the same road. Both are active for funerals, stone-settings and visiting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/bushey-cemetery|title=Bushey Cemetery &#124; United Synagogue|website=www.theus.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 a \u00a36.12 m extension was built, as the 43,000 grave spaces in the old cemetery were nearly full, and another 17,000 were thought necessary to provide for the next 50 years. {{convert|16|acre}} of new land were laid out by the landscape architects J and L Gibbons, with two prayer halls, offices and a mortuary. There are also separate rooms for the [[Cohanim]], who are not permitted to be in the same space as the coffin, but may view proceedings through glass walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2018/jan/07/bushey-jewish-cemetery-extension-review|title=Bushey Jewish Cemetery review \u2013 a place of dignity and ease|first=Rowan|last=Moore|date=7 January 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- *** Please remember to add the Category:People from Bushey to the page of anybody you add to this list *** -->\n{{div col |colwidth=30em}}\n*[[George Michael]], musician, [[Wham!]], attended Bushey Meads School\n*[[Andrew Ridgeley]], musician, [[Wham!]], attended Bushey Meads School\n*[[R. D. Blackmore]], novelist, lived briefly in Bushey\n*[[Freddie Bunce]], footballer\n*[[Dave Cash (disc jockey)|Dave Cash]], disc jockey, born in Bushey\n*[[Helen Cherry]], actor, born in Bushey\n*[[Peter Copley]], actor, born in Bushey\n*[[Oliver Dowden]], Member of Parliament for Hertsmere\n*[[John Gale (poker player)|John Gale]], poker player\n*[[Divina Galica]], skier and racing driver, born in Bushey Heath\n*[[Phil Gillies]], Canadian politician, born in Bushey\n*[[Hubert von Herkomer]], artist, owner of [[Lululaund]]\n*[[Shirlie Holliman]], musician, of [[Pepsi & Shirlie]], attended [[Bushey Meads School]]\n*[[Tom Howard (special effects)|Tom Howard]], Oscar-winning film special effects man, lived in Bushey from 1946 until his death in 1985\n*[[Lucy Kemp-Welch]], artist\n*[[Bill Kerr]], actor and radio broadcaster lived in the high street. He starred as Flight Lieutenant H. B. \"Micky\" Martin, pilot of \"Popsie\" in the ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|Dam Busters]]''\n*[[Simon Le Bon]], musician, [[Duran Duran]], born in Bushey\n*[[A. E. Matthews]], character actor, lived in Bushey until his death. He has a blue plaque in Little Bushey Lane.\n*Dr [[Thomas Monro (art collector)|Thomas Monro]], Principal Physician of [[Bethlem Hospital|Bedlam]] and who attended on [[King George III]] in his last illness, settled his family here in the 19th century\n*[[Tony O'Malley (musician)|Tony O'Malley]], musician, born in Bushey\n*[[Josef Perl]], Holocaust survivor, lives in Bushey\n*[[Sid Phillips (musician)|Sid Phillips]], musician, band leader, lived in Bushey Heath\n*[[Simon Phillips (drummer)|Simon Phillips]], musician, drummer [[Toto (band)|Toto]], lived in Bushey Heath\n*[[Roy Plomley]], radio presenter, created [[Desert Island Discs]] whilst living in a cottage at Little Bushey Lane\n*[[Michael Portillo]], journalist, broadcaster and former politician, born in Bushey\n*[[Mark Ramprakash]], cricketer, born in Bushey\n*[[William Hurst Rees]], surveyor\n*[[Mich\u00e8le Roberts]], writer\n*[[Gilbert Taylor]], cinematographer, born in Bushey Heath\n*[[Henry Wylde]], conductor and musician\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Twin town==\nBushey has been twinned with German town [[Landsberg am Lech]] in Bavaria ([[Southern Germany]]) for its historical link. To Landsberg belonged the native village, Waal, of artist ''Herkomer'' detailed above. The towns retain links for mayoral duties and school exchange trips.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bushey Hall]]\n*[[Bushey Hall Golf Club]]\n*[[Bushey Museum]]\n*[[Bushey railway station]]\n*[[RAF Bushey Hall]]\n\n==Nearest places==\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring areas'''\n|Northwest = [[Watford]]\n|North     = [[Aldenham]]\n|Northeast = [[Aldenham|Patchetts Green]] and [[Letchmore Heath]]\n|West      = [[Oxhey]]\n|Centre    = Bushey\n|East      = [[Aldenham|Aldenham Park]] [[Elstree|Elstree Aerodrome, Hilfield Park Reservoir, Aldenham Reservoir and Elstree]]\n|Southwest = Merry Hill, 76 ha. woodland managed by the Woodland Trust, Haydon Hill then [[Carpenders Park]]\n|South     =  [[Headstone, London|Headstone]]<br>[[Harrow Weald]] <br />\n(across Hartsbourne Golf & Country Club; [[Grim's Ditch (Harrow)|Grim's Ditch]]; [[Harrow Weald Common]])\n|Southeast = [[Stanmore Common]] and [[Bentley Priory]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{cite book|last=Youngs|first=FA|title=Guide to the Local Administrative Units of England|publisher=Royal Historical Society|location=London|origyear=1981|year=1991|volume=1 (of 2)}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43267 |title=Parishes: Bushey |editor=William Page |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |date=1908 |work=A History of the County of Hertford: volume 2 |accessdate=28 April 2014 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Hertfordshire}}\n{{Civil parishes of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Hertsmere]]\n[[Category:Highest points of English counties]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Category:Unparished areas in Hertfordshire", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bushey"}
{"title_page": "Chris Eaton (Canadian musician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Chris Eaton\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1971}}<!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place         = [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]], Canada\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Indie rock]]\n| occupation          = [[Singer-songwriter]]<br />Novelist\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Rock Plaza Central]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Chris Eaton''' (born 1971 in [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]]) is the founder and lead vocalist of [[Toronto]]-based [[indie rock]] band [[Rock Plaza Central]], as well as a novelist. Chris is not an American astronomer nor a discoverer of numerous moons, comets and minor planets in the outer Solar System.\n\n== Music career ==\nEaton began as a solo artist, with various musicians backing him, often using musical improvisation. In 2003, the current line-up of Rock Plaza Central formed during such a gig in Toronto, and they recorded their first album in that incarnation only a month later.  Their second album, ''[[Are We Not Horses]]'', was favorably reviewed by influential music journal [[Pitchfork Media]].\n\n== Writing career ==\nEaton is also a published author.<ref>Teo, Mark (December 1, 2009). \"[http://www.chartattack.com/news/77353/rock-plaza-centrals-chris-eaton-working-on-new-book-about-chris-eatons Rock Plaza Central's Chris Eaton Working On New Book... About Chris Eatons]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\", [[Chartattack.com]]. Retrieved December 26, 2010.</ref><ref>Hughes, Josiah (December 1, 2009). \"[http://exclaim.ca/News/rock_plaza_central_take_break_as_front-man_chris_eaton_wraps_up_new_novel Rock Plaza Central Take a Break As Front-Man Chris Eaton Wraps Up New Novel]\", ''[[Exclaim!]]''. Retrieved December 26, 2010.</ref> His first novel ''The Inactivist'' (2003), has been required reading on two university courses at [[McGill University]] in [[Montreal]], as well as a graduate English course at the University of South Alabama.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} His second novel, ''The Grammar Architect'' (2006), is a \"cover\" of a [[Thomas Hardy]] book, ''[[A Pair of Blue Eyes]]'',<ref>Medley, Mark (June 23, 2009). \"Multi-hyphenate melodies\", ''[[National Post]]'', p. A2.</ref> using some of the plot, imagery, themes and even some passages of the original and creating something new and personal out of that.\n\nLetters To Thomas Pynchon is a short fiction collection published as an eBook with Joyland: A hub for short fiction in 2010.\n\nIn 2013, Eaton published his third novel called ''Chris Eaton, a Biography'' with [[Book*hug|Book*hug Press]]. Critical response was generally quite positive, with profiles in prominent national media like the [[National Post]] and [[Toronto Star]]. Martin Patriquin of [[MacLean's]] wrote \"Nabokov could write about his back porch and make it interesting; Chris Eaton does much the same with his fellow Chris Eatons\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patriquin|first1=Martin|title=Chris Eaton, a Biography|url=http://www.macleans.ca/culture/books/chris-eaton-a-biography/}}</ref> and [[The Winnipeg Review]], while critical of the confusion of the conceit, praised the prose: \"It's work, in other words, but Eaton's language is so good, managing that easygoing poetry that feels made from the thoughts of people who don't know they're being written, that you forgive him for it. Chris Eaton is threaded with so much of this kind of silver that it feels like he must just open the tap and let it pour.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Rioux|first1=Josh|title=Chris Eaton, a Biography by Chris Eaton|url=http://www.winnipegreview.com/wp/2013/07/chris-eaton-a-biography-by-chris-eaton/}}</ref> The novel was included in many year-end lists, including the ''Toronto Star'', ''[[Quill & Quire]]'' and [[Quarterly Conversation]] while also being included in [[Steven Moore (author)|Steven Moore]]'s ''The Novel: an Alternative History'', Volume 2.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bursey|first1=Jeff|title=TQC Favorite Reads of 2013|url=http://conversationalreading.com/tqc-favorite-reads-of-2013-jeff-bursey/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Beattie|first1=Stephen W.|title=Books of the Year 2013|url=http://www.quillandquire.com/books-year/2013/12/02/books-of-the-year-2013-review-editor-steven-w-beattie-makes-his-picks/}}</ref>\n\nEaton's fourth novel, ''Symphony No. 3,'' based on the life of composer [[Camille Saint-Sa\u00ebns]], was published in 2019 by Book*hug Press and was listed as a finalist for the 2020 New Brunswick Book Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bookhugpress.ca/shop/books/symphony-no-3-by-chris-eaton/|title=Symphony No. 3 by Chris Eaton|publisher=Book*hug Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nbbookawards.wixsite.com/info|title=New Brunswick Book Awards Shortlisted Titles Announced|publisher=New Brunswick Book Awards|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The New York critic David Gutowski called it \"one of the year's finest novels, symphonic in structure and spectacular on a sentence level.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.largeheartedboy.com/blog/archive/2019/10/chris_eatons_pl.html|title=Chris Eaton's Playlist for His Novel \"Symphony No. 3\"|publisher=largehearted boy|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.frye.ca/chris-eaton?lang=en|title=Frye Festival|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''Quill and Quire'' reviewer Jos\u00e9 Teodoro described the novel's narrative voice as one that is \"capable of delivering an unrelenting battery of fireworks that leaves the reader dazzled and exhausted...It\u2019s intended as neither mere praise nor outright dismissal to state that novels are rarely infused with this combination of piercing intelligence and flights of tedium.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillandquire.com/review/symphony-no-3/|title=Symphony No. 3 by Chris Eaton|author=Teodoro, Jos\u00e9|publisher=Quill and Quire|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''Toronto Star'' reviewer Brett Josef Grubisic wrote that the novel reminded him of the flamboyant, American musician [[Liberace]]. \"Tasty in small bites and impressive as an antic literary performance, the novel\u2019s structure gradually buckles under the sheer mass of extravagant decoration. As with Liberace\u2019s mirror walls etched with [[Aubrey Beardsley]] drawings, sensory overload produces diminishing returns.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2019/11/15/fictional-bio-of-romantic-era-composer-saint-sans-features-liberace-like-opulence-and-adventures.html|title=Fictional bio of Romantic-era composer Saint-Sa\u00ebns features Liberace-like opulence and adventures|author=Grubisic, Brett Josef|publisher=Toronto Star|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''Globe and Mail'' reviewer Jade Colbert called it \"a dense text, and it reproduces the prejudices of ''[[fin de si\u00e8cle]]'' Europe, which can make for difficult reading, though there are also sections when this novel opens up and sings.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books/article-twelve-books-to-add-to-your-2020-reading-list/?fbclid=IwAR1T93Eo5pA1XqDCs-DOrD83DlcW9FEiUx4zrWi4tXyXyA6bcHrIN3bX_Zg|author=Colbert, Jade|title=Twelve books from independent publishers to add to your 2020 reading list|publisher=Globe and Mail|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eaton, Chris}}\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian rock singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Moncton]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n\n\n{{Canada-singer-stub}}\n{{singer-songwriter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Chris Eaton\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1971}}<!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place         = [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]], Canada\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Indie rock]]\n| occupation          = [[Singer-songwriter]]<br />Novelist\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Rock Plaza Central]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Chris Eaton''' (born 1971 in [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]]) is the founder and lead vocalist of [[Toronto]]-based [[indie rock]] band [[Rock Plaza Central]], as well as a novelist. Chris is not an American astronomer nor a discoverer of numerous moons, comets and minor planets in the outer Solar System.\n\n== Music career ==\nEaton began as a solo artist, with various musicians backing him, often using musical improvisation. In 2003, the current line-up of Rock Plaza Central formed during such a gig in Toronto, and they recorded their first album in that incarnation only a month later.  Their second album, ''[[Are We Not Horses]]'', was favorably reviewed by influential music journal [[Pitchfork Media]].\n\n== Writing career ==\nEaton is also a published author.<ref>Teo, Mark (December 1, 2009). \"[http://www.chartattack.com/news/77353/rock-plaza-centrals-chris-eaton-working-on-new-book-about-chris-eatons Rock Plaza Central's Chris Eaton Working On New Book... About Chris Eatons]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\", [[Chartattack.com]]. Retrieved December 26, 2010.</ref><ref>Hughes, Josiah (December 1, 2009). \"[http://exclaim.ca/News/rock_plaza_central_take_break_as_front-man_chris_eaton_wraps_up_new_novel Rock Plaza Central Take a Break As Front-Man Chris Eaton Wraps Up New Novel]\", ''[[Exclaim!]]''. Retrieved December 26, 2010.</ref> His first novel ''The Inactivist'' (2003), has been required reading on two university courses at [[McGill University]] in [[Montreal]], as well as a graduate English course at the University of South Alabama.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} His second novel, ''The Grammar Architect'' (2006), is a \"cover\" of a [[Thomas Hardy]] book, ''[[A Pair of Blue Eyes]]'',<ref>Medley, Mark (June 23, 2009). \"Multi-hyphenate melodies\", ''[[National Post]]'', p. A2.</ref> using some of the plot, imagery, themes and even some passages of the original and creating something new and personal out of that.\n\nLetters To Thomas Pynchon is a short fiction collection published as an eBook with Joyland: A hub for short fiction in 2010.\n\nIn 2013, Eaton published his third novel called ''Chris Eaton, a Biography'' with [[Book*hug|Book*hug Press]]. Critical response was generally quite positive, with profiles in prominent national media like the [[National Post]] and [[Toronto Star]]. Martin Patriquin of [[MacLean's]] wrote \"Nabokov could write about his back porch and make it interesting; Chris Eaton does much the same with his fellow Chris Eatons\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patriquin|first1=Martin|title=Chris Eaton, a Biography|url=http://www.macleans.ca/culture/books/chris-eaton-a-biography/}}</ref> and [[The Winnipeg Review]], while critical of the confusion of the conceit, praised the prose: \"It's work, in other words, but Eaton's language is so good, managing that easygoing poetry that feels made from the thoughts of people who don't know they're being written, that you forgive him for it. Chris Eaton is threaded with so much of this kind of silver that it feels like he must just open the tap and let it pour.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Rioux|first1=Josh|title=Chris Eaton, a Biography by Chris Eaton|url=http://www.winnipegreview.com/wp/2013/07/chris-eaton-a-biography-by-chris-eaton/}}</ref> The novel was included in many year-end lists, including the ''Toronto Star'', [[''Quill & Quire'']] and [[Quarterly Conversation]] while also being included in [[Steven Moore (author)|Steven Moore]]'s ''The Novel: an Alternative History'', Volume 2.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bursey|first1=Jeff|title=TQC Favorite Reads of 2013|url=http://conversationalreading.com/tqc-favorite-reads-of-2013-jeff-bursey/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Beattie|first1=Stephen W.|title=Books of the Year 2013|url=http://www.quillandquire.com/books-year/2013/12/02/books-of-the-year-2013-review-editor-steven-w-beattie-makes-his-picks/}}</ref>\n\nEaton's fourth novel, ''Symphony No. 3,'' based on the life of composer [[Camille Saint-Sa\u00ebns]], was published in 2019 by Book*hug Press and was listed as a finalist for the 2020 New Brunswick Book Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bookhugpress.ca/shop/books/symphony-no-3-by-chris-eaton/|title=Symphony No. 3 by Chris Eaton|publisher=Book*hug Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nbbookawards.wixsite.com/info|title=New Brunswick Book Awards Shortlisted Titles Announced|publisher=New Brunswick Book Awards|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The New York critic David Gutowski called it \"one of the year's finest novels, symphonic in structure and spectacular on a sentence level.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.largeheartedboy.com/blog/archive/2019/10/chris_eatons_pl.html|title=Chris Eaton's Playlist for His Novel \"Symphony No. 3\"|publisher=largehearted boy|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.frye.ca/chris-eaton?lang=en|title=Frye Festival|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''Quill and Quire'' reviewer Jos\u00e9 Teodoro described the novel's narrative voice as one that is \"capable of delivering an unrelenting battery of fireworks that leaves the reader dazzled and exhausted...It\u2019s intended as neither mere praise nor outright dismissal to state that novels are rarely infused with this combination of piercing intelligence and flights of tedium.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quillandquire.com/review/symphony-no-3/|title=Symphony No. 3 by Chris Eaton|author=Teodoro, Jos\u00e9|publisher=Quill and Quire|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''Toronto Star'' reviewer Brett Josef Grubisic wrote that the novel reminded him of the flamboyant, American musician [[Liberace]]. \"Tasty in small bites and impressive as an antic literary performance, the novel\u2019s structure gradually buckles under the sheer mass of extravagant decoration. As with Liberace\u2019s mirror walls etched with [[Aubrey Beardsley]] drawings, sensory overload produces diminishing returns.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2019/11/15/fictional-bio-of-romantic-era-composer-saint-sans-features-liberace-like-opulence-and-adventures.html|title=Fictional bio of Romantic-era composer Saint-Sa\u00ebns features Liberace-like opulence and adventures|author=Grubisic, Brett Josef|publisher=Toronto Star|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> ''Globe and Mail'' reviewer Jade Colbert called it \"a dense text, and it reproduces the prejudices of ''[[fin de si\u00e8cle]]'' Europe, which can make for difficult reading, though there are also sections when this novel opens up and sings.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books/article-twelve-books-to-add-to-your-2020-reading-list/?fbclid=IwAR1T93Eo5pA1XqDCs-DOrD83DlcW9FEiUx4zrWi4tXyXyA6bcHrIN3bX_Zg|author=Colbert, Jade|title=Twelve books from independent publishers to add to your 2020 reading list|publisher=Globe and Mail|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eaton, Chris}}\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian rock singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Moncton]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n\n\n{{Canada-singer-stub}}\n{{singer-songwriter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bwark", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixing minor error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Eaton_(Canadian_musician)"}
{"title_page": "List of massacres in China", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}The following is a list of [[massacre]]s that have occurred in China. The massacres are grouped for different periods. The lists are incomplete.\n\n== Imperial China (221 BC-1912 AD) ==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n|-\n! style=\"width:120px;\" |Name\n! style=\"width:65px;\" |Date\n! style=\"width:120px;\" |Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\" |Deaths\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n|[[Yangzhou massacre (760)]]\n|760\n|[[Yangzhou]]\n|{{ntsh|120000}}Several thousands\n|Foreign merchants: [[Arabs]] and [[Persian people|Persians]] were killed<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yangzhou_massacre_(760)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Guangzhou massacre]] \n|878\u2013879\n|[[Guangzhou]]\n|{{ntsh|120000}}120,000 - 200,000\n|Foreign merchants: [[Arabs]], [[Persian people|Persians]], [[Christians]] and [[Jews]] were killed.<ref>https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_ObcNAAAAIAAJ/page/n5/mode/2up</ref>\n|-\n|Sichuan massacre\n|1645-1646\n|[[Sichuan]]\n|{{ntsh|1,000,000}}1,000,000 est.<ref name=\"parsons\" />\n|There is no reliable figure, but estimated 1 million out of 3 million [[Sichuanese people|Sichuanese]] were massacred mainly by the army of [[Zhang Xianzhong]].<ref name=\"parsons\">{{cite journal |author=James B. Parsons |date=May 1957 |title=The Culmination of a Chinese Peasant Rebellion: Chang Hsien-chung in Szechwan, 1644-46 |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?aid=7001496 |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |publisher=Association for Asian Studies |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=387\u2013400 |doi=10.2307/2941233 |jstor=2941233}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Yangzhou massacre]]\n|1645\n|[[Yangzhou]]\n|{{ntsh|299999}}=?< 300,000 (modern estimate)<ref>Struve (1993) (note at p. 269), following a 1964 article by Zhang Defang, notes that the entire city's population at the time was not likely to be more than 300,000, and that of the entire Yangzhou Prefecture, 800,000.</ref>\n|\n|-\n|[[Dzungar genocide]]\n|1755\u20131757\n|[[Dzungar Khanate]]\n|{{ntsh|540000}}540,000<ref>Geometric mean of 480 and 600 thousand rounded up to nearest ten thousand.</ref>\n|480,000 to 600,000 deaths: 80% of Dzungar population killed.<ref>{{cite book|author=L. J. Newby|title=The Empire And the Khanate: A Political History of Qing Relations With Khoqand C1760-1860|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KTmO416hNQ8C&pg=PA15#v=snippet&q=banners%20junghars%201757&f=false|year=2005|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-14550-8|pages=15\u2013}}</ref>\n\n|-\n|[[Ningpo Massacre]] \n|1800s\n|[[Ningbo]]\n|{{ntsh|40}}40\n|Cantonese pirates supported by the Qing massacred 40 Portuguese pirates.\n|-\n|[[Tianjin Massacre]] \n|1870\n|[[Tianjin]]\n|{{ntsh|40}}60\n|Chinese crowds killing Chinese christians, French priests and nuns\n|-\n|[[Jindandao incident]]\n|1891\n|[[Inner Mongolia]]\n|{{ntsh|150,000}}150,000 - 500,000\n|Ethnic tensions led a Chinese secret society, Jindandao, to revolt and kill 150,000 - 500,000 Mongols.\n|-\n|[[Port Arthur massacre (China)|Port Arthur massacre]]\n|1894, November 21\n|[[L\u00fcshunkou]], [[Liaoning]]\n|{{ntsh|4500}}4500\n|1000\u201320,000{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n|-\n|[[Kucheng Massacre]]\n|1895, August 1\n|[[Gutian County|Gutian]], [[Fujian]]\n|{{ntsh|11}}11\n|11 British missionaries killed by a fasting folk religious group on August 1, 1895\n|-\n|[[Juye_Incident|Juye Incident]]\n|1897, November 1 - 2\n|[[Juye County]] [[Shandong]]\n|{{ntsh|11}}2\n|2 German missionaries killed by members of the [[Big_Swords_Society|Big Swords Society]]\n|-\n|[[Taiyuan Massacre]]\n|1900, July\n|[[Taiyuan]], [[Shanxi]]\n|{{ntsh|45}} 45\n| 45 Christian men, women and children\n|}\n\n== Republic of China (1912\u20131949) ==\n\n=== 1912\u20131937 ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Shanghai massacre of 1927]]\n|1927, April 12\n|[[Shanghai]]\n|{{ntsh|1200}}1200\n|300\u2013400 direct deaths. 5000 missing\n|-\n|[[Anti-communist mass killings#China|Kuomintang Anti-Communist massacre]]\n|1928\n|Nationwide in [[China]]\n|{{ntsh|300000}}300,000<ref name=\"Barnouin38\">Barnouin, Barbara and Yu Changgen. ''Zhou Enlai: A Political Life.'' Hong Kong: Chinese University of Hong Kong, 2006. {{ISBN|962-996-280-2}}.  Retrieved at <https://books.google.com/books?id=NztlWQeXf2IC&printsec=frontcover&dq=zhou+enlai&hl=en&ei=wBkuTdKyB4H_8AaJucigAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false> on March 12, 2011.  p.38</ref>\n|Mass executions of both alleged and actual [[communist]]s by the nationalist [[Kuomintang]].\n|-\n|Communist purge in [[Jiangxi\u2013Fujian Soviet]] ([[Chinese Civil War|Chinese civil war]])\n|1931-1935\n|Most parts of [[Ganzhou]] and every part of [[Tingzhou fu|Tingzhou]]\n|{{ntsh|700000}}700,000<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L_bQX73aOvcC&pg=PA133|title=Mao: The Unknown Story|page=133}}</ref>\n|Occurred in the mountainous parts which are almost entirely only populated by Hakkas of Jiangxi and Fujian.\n|-\n||[[Kizil massacre]]\n|1933, June\n|near [[Kashgar]], [[Xinjiang]]\n|{{ntsh|800}}800\n|\n|-\n||[[Battle of Kashgar (1934)|Kashgar massacre]]\n|1934\n|[[Kashgar]], [[Xinjiang]]\n|{{ntsh|4000}}2,000-8,000\n|\n|}\n\n=== 1937\u20131945 (Sino-Japanese War) ===\n{{See also|Second Sino-Japanese War|World War II}}\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Nanjing Massacre]]\n|1937, December 13\n|[[Nanjing]]\n|{{nts|110000}}<ref>Geometric mean of 40 and 300 thousand rounded to nearest 10 thousand.</ref>\n| 40,000\u2013300,000 deaths by [[Imperial Japanese Army|Japanese military]].The death toll is disputed, ranging from some Japanese claims of several hundred,<ref>[[Masaaki Tanaka]] claims that very few citizens were killed, and that the massacre is in fact a fabrication in his book ''[http://www.ne.jp/asahi/unko/tamezou/nankin/whatreally/ \u201cNankin gyakusatsu\u201d no kyok\u014d] (The \"Nanking Massacre\" as Fabrication)''.</ref> to the Chinese claim of a non-combatant death toll of 300,000.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/2001/0820/p1s3-woap.html \"Why the past still separates China and Japan\"] Robert Marquand (August 20, 2001) Christian Science Monitor. States an estimate of 300,000 dead.</ref> Most other nations believe the death toll to be between 150,000\u2013300,000, based on the [[Nanjing War Crimes Tribunal]] verdict.\n|-\n|[[Changjiao massacre]]\n|1943, May 9\u201312\n|[[Changjiao]], [[Hunan]]\n|{{ntsh|30000}}30,000\n|Conducted by [[Imperial Japanese Army|Japanese military]].\n|}\n\n=== 1945\u20131949 (Civil War) ===\n{{See also|Chinese Civil War}}\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[February 28 incident]]\n|1947, February 28\u2013May 16\n|[[Taiwan Province|Taiwan]]\n|5,000 to 28,000\n|Beginning of the [[White Terror (Taiwan)|White Terror]] campaign. The Chinese Kuomintang-led government imposed [[Martial law in Taiwan|martial law]] until 1987.\n|}\n\n== People's Republic of China (1949-present) ==\n\n=== 1949\u20131966 ===\n{{See also|Great Chinese Famine}}\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Chinese Land Reform]]\n|1948\u20131951\n|Nationwide\n|1,000,000 \u2013 4,500,000\n|Launched by [[Mao Zedong]] and the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC). Liquidation of the landlord class in [[struggle sessions]]. \n|-\n|[[Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries]]\n|1950\u20131951\n|Nationwide\n|712,000 \u2013 2,000,000<ref name=\"Yang Kuisong\">{{cite journal|author=[[Yang Kuisong]]|year=2008|title=Reconsidering the Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=1809176|journal=[[The China Quarterly]]|volume=193|pages=102\u2013121|doi=10.1017/S0305741008000064}}{{paywall}}[https://chinachange.org/2011/11/28/reconsidering-the-campaign-to-suppress-counterrevolutionaries/ summary] at China Change blog</ref><ref name=\"Mao's Killing Quotas\">{{cite web|url=http://hrichina.org/public/PDFs/CRF.4.2005/CRF-2005-4_Quota.pdf|title=Mao's \"Killing Quotas.\" Human Rights in China (HRIC). 26 September 2005, at Shandong University|last=Changyu|first=Li|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090729194758/http://www.hrichina.org/public/PDFs/CRF.4.2005/CRF-2005-4_Quota.pdf|archivedate=29 July 2009}}</ref>\n|Launched by Mao Zedong and CPC.\n|-\n|[[Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns]]\n|1951\u20131952\n|Nationwide\n|\n|Exact death toll is unknown. In Shanghai alone, from January 25 to April 1, 1952, at least 876 people committed suicides.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cuhk.edu.hk/ics/21c/media/articles/c092-200502054.pdf|title=\u6267\u653f\u7684\u9053\u5fb7\u56f0\u5883\u4e0e\u7a81\u56f4\u4e4b\u9053\u2014\u2014\u201c\u4e09\u53cd\u4e94\u53cd\u201d\u8fd0\u52a8\u89e3\u6790|author=Zhang|first=Ming|date=|website=|publisher=Chinese University of Hong Kong|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://history.sohu.com/20130726/n381843451.shtml|title=\u90a3\u4e00\u5e74\uff0c\u4e2d\u56fd\u5546\u8d3e\u5343\u4eba\u8df3\u697c \u5168\u5bb6\u5171\u8d74\u9ec4\u6cc9\uff08\u56fe\uff09|author=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=\u641c\u72d0|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801001234/http://history.sohu.com/20130726/n381843451.shtml|archive-date=2013-08-01|accessdate=2019-11-22|dead-url=}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://talk.ifeng.com/project/special/guoqingjie/zuixin/detail_2012_09/28/17984862_0.shtml|title=\u4e09\u53cd\u4e94\u53cd\uff1a\u8d44\u4ea7\u9636\u7ea7\u547d\u8fd0\u7684\u7ec8\u7ed3|author=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u7f51|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031150023/http://talk.ifeng.com/project/special/guoqingjie/zuixin/detail_2012_09/28/17984862_0.shtml|archive-date=2017-10-31|accessdate=2019-11-22|dead-url=}}</ref> Launched by Mao Zedong and CPC. \n|-\n|[[Sufan movement]]\n|1955\u20131956\n|Nationwide\n|53,000<ref>{{Cite book|last=Luo\uff09|first=\u7f57\u6170\u5e74 \uff08William|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ooIIDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA153&lpg=PA153&dq=%E8%82%83%E5%8F%8D%E8%BF%90%E5%8A%A8+5.3%E4%B8%87%E4%BA%BA+%E6%AD%BB%E4%BA%A1&source=bl&ots=5mzzTCF8NM&sig=ACfU3U1AH9BF_xjecdYgdIin8-uGMX1Qlg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj134mUsdDoAhWCKM0KHX2ODbMQ6AEwAXoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=%E8%82%83%E5%8F%8D%E8%BF%90%E5%8A%A8%205.3%E4%B8%87%E4%BA%BA%20%E6%AD%BB%E4%BA%A1&f=false|title=\u534a\u8d44\u672c\u8bba \uff08Semi-Capital\uff09(\u7b2c\u4e03\u7248): \u534a\u8d44\u672c\u4e3b\u4e49\u4e0e\u4e2d\u56fd \uff08Semi-Capitalism in China\uff09|date=2018-03-30|publisher=\u4e16\u754c\u534e\u8bed\u51fa\u7248\u793e|isbn=978-1-940266-12-1|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.storm.mg/article/446880|title=\u9673\u662d\u5357\u5c08\u6b04\uff1a\u9047\u5230\u4e2d\u5171\u5c31\u5931\u61b6\uff01\u570b\u6c11\u9ee8\u9084\u80fd\u9a19\u81ea\u5df1\u591a\u4e45\uff1f-\u98a8\u50b3\u5a92|last=Storm.mg|date=2018-06-09|website=www.storm.mg|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|Launched by Mao Zedong and CPC.\n|-\n|[[Anti-Rightist Campaign]]\n|1957\n|Nationwide\n|\n|Exact death toll is unknown. Official statistics shows that at least 550,000 people were purged and many died.<ref name=\"silence\">{{cite web|url=http://cmp.hku.hk/2009/09/10/1740/|title=Uneasy silences punctuate 60th anniversary coverage|publisher=China Media Project|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611085558/http://cmp.hku.hk/2009/09/10/1740/|archivedate=2010-06-11|accessdate=2009-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vidal|first=Christine|date=2016|title=The 1957-1958 Anti-Rightist Campaign in China: History and Memory (1978-2014)|url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-01306892/document|url-status=live|journal=HAL-SHS|volume=|pages=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128050256/https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-01306892/document|archive-date=2019-11-28|access-date=2019-11-28|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/the-silence-that-preceded-chinas-great-leap-into-famine-51898077/|title=The Silence that Preceded China\u2019s Great Leap into Famine|last=King|first=Gilbert|website=Smithsonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014232813/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/the-silence-that-preceded-chinas-great-leap-into-famine-51898077/|archive-date=2019-10-14|access-date=2019-11-28}}</ref> Launched by Mao Zedong and CPC.\n|-\n|[[Socialist Education Movement]]\n|1963\u20131965\n|Nationwide\n|77,560<ref>{{Cite book|last=Yang|first=Jishen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4d4qDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT67&lpg=PT67&dq=%E5%9B%9B%E6%B8%85%E8%BF%90%E5%8A%A8+77560&source=bl&ots=225yUBw_7e&sig=ACfU3U0ulCZv1-yRXfQDGSL6XMBILQ8aDw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjZy5-opK3nAhWAl3IEHeEpAF0Q6AEwAHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%E5%9B%9B%E6%B8%85%E8%BF%90%E5%8A%A8%2077560&f=false|title=\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986: \u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d\u5386\u53f2|date=2017-07-04|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=zh}}</ref>\n|Launched by Mao Zedong.\n|}\n\n=== 1966\u20131976 (Cultural Revolution) ===\n{{See also|Cultural_Revolution#Massacres_and_cannibalism}}[[Cultural Revolution]] was launched by [[Mao Zedong]] in May 1966, with the help of the [[Cultural Revolution Group]]. Some of the massacres occurred during the [[Violent Struggle|Violent Struggles]] (300,000-500,000 deaths), [[Struggle session|struggle sessions]] or political purges such as [[Cleansing the Class Ranks]] (0.5-1.5 million deaths). Chinese scholars have estimated that at least 300 thousand people were killed in these massacres.<ref name=\":47\">{{Cite book|last=\u6768\u7ee7\u7ef3|title=\u300a\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986-\u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u9769\u5927\u9769\u547d\u53f2\u300b|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|title=\u300a\u6587\u9769\u5927\u5c60\u6740\u300b|publisher=\u5f00\u653e\u6742\u5fd7\u51fa\u7248\u793e|year=2002|isbn=9789627934097}}</ref> Massacres in [[Guangxi province|Guangxi Province]] and [[Guangdong Province]] were among the most serious; in Guangxi, the official documents of at least 43 counties report local massacres with 15 of them recording a death toll of over 1000, while in Guangdong at least 28 counties report local massacres with 6 of them recording over 1000 deaths.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Su|date=2006|title=\u201c\u6587\u9769\u201d\u4e2d\u7684\u96c6\u4f53\u5c60\u6740\uff1a\u4e09\u7701\u7814\u7a76|url=https://www.modernchinastudies.org/cn/issues/past-issues/93-mcs-2006-issue-3/974-2012-01-05-15-35-10.html|journal=Modern China Studies|language=zh|volume=3|pages=|via=}}</ref> The following table only includes major massacres which have been well documented in literature. \n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Red August]]\n|August \u2013 September 1966\n|[[Beijing]]\n|1,772<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phillips|first=Tom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/11/the-cultural-revolution-50-years-on-all-you-need-to-know-about-chinas-political-convulsion|title=The Cultural Revolution: all you need to know about China's political convulsion|date=2016-05-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n| Origin of the [[Red Terror]] of the Chinese Cultural Revolution, triggering \"[[Daxing Massacre]]\" which killed 325 people in a few days. Statistics from 1985 showed a death toll of over 10,000 during the Red August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2011/09/201109160825.shtml|title=\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u201c\u975e\u6b63\u5e38\u6b7b\u4ea1\u201d\u4e86\u591a\u5c11\u4eba\uff1f ---- \u8bfb\u82cf\u626c\u7684\u300a\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u4e2d\u56fd\u519c\u6751\u7684\u96c6\u4f53\u5c60\u6740\u300b/\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last=Song|first=Yongyi|date=|website=Boxun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Guangxi Massacre]]\n|1966\u20131976\n|[[Guangxi]]\n|100,000 \u2013 150,000<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/china-cultrev-04292016134149.html|title=Interview: 'People Were Eaten by The Revolutionary Masses'|website=Radio Free Asia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhcqw.com/34/8938.html|title=\u6211\u53c2\u4e0e\u5904\u7406\u5e7f\u897f\u6587\u9769\u9057\u7559\u95ee\u9898|last=Yan|first=Lebin|date=|website=www.yhcqw.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|Massive [[cannibalism]] occurred.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Inner Mongolia incident]]\n|1967\u20131969\n|[[Inner Mongolia]]\n|16,632 \u2013 100,000<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-mass-killings-during-chinese-cultural-revolution-1966-1976|title=Chronology of Mass Killings during the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|website=www.sciencespo.fr|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n|Mostly [[Mongols]].\n|-\n|Qinghai Massacre\n|February 1967\n|[[Qinghai]]\n|173<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-mass-killings-during-chinese-cultural-revolution-1966-1976.html|title=Chronology of Mass Killings during the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|last=Song|first=Yongyi|date=|website=SciencesPo|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n|Conducted by [[People's Liberation Army]].<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite book