{"title_page": "Avoca Lodge", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name =Avoca Lodge\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | designated_other1 = Colorado\n  | designated_other1_date = \n  | designated_other1_number = 5DV.696\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n  | image = Avoca Lodge Denver CO.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 2690 S. Wadsworth Blvd., [[Denver, Colorado]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|39|40|5|N|105|4|50|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Colorado#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1897\n  | architecture= Foursquare\n  | added = January 26, 1990\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=89002373<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Avoca Lodge''', known as '''The Molly Brown Summer House''', is a [[Registered Historic Places|Registered Historic Place]] in southwest [[Denver, Colorado]] near Bear Creek.  The home served as a summer retreat for [[philanthropist]], [[socialite]], and [[activist]] [[Margaret Brown]] and her husband [[James Joseph Brown]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Iversen|first1=Kristen|title=Molly Brown: Unraveling the Myth|date=1999|publisher=Johnson Books|location=Boulder|isbn=1555662374|pages=110\u2013112}}<!--|accessdate=5 February 2015--></ref> Brown was known as \"The Unsinkable Molly Brown\" because she survived the sinking of the [[RMS Titanic]]. It is open to the public for rental and tours.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mollybrownsummerhouse.com/ Molly Brown Summer House]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080513030749/http://www.historicdistricts.com/CO/Denver/state.html National Register of Historic Places, Colorado, Denver]\n\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Denver]]\n[[Category:Houses in Denver]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Museums in Denver]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1897]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Colorado]]\n[[Category:James Joseph Brown family residences]]\n\n\n{{Colorado-museum-stub}}\n{{Colorado-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Denver-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name =Avoca Lodge\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | designated_other1 = Colorado\n  | designated_other1_date = \n  | designated_other1_number = 5DV.696\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n  | image = Avoca Lodge Denver CO.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= 2690 S. Wadsworth Blvd., [[Denver, Colorado]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|39|40|5|N|105|4|50|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Colorado#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1897\n  | architecture= Foursquare\n  | added = January 26, 1990\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=89002373<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Avoca Lodge''', known as '''The Molly Brown Summer House''', is a [[Registered Historic Places|Registered Historic Place]] in southwest [[Denver, Colorado]] near Bear Creek.  The home served as a summer retreat for [[philanthropist]], [[socialite]], and [[activist]] [[Margaret Brown]] and her husband [[James Joseph Brown]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Iversen|first1=Kristen|title=Molly Brown: Unraveling the Myth|date=1999|publisher=Johnson Books|location=Boulder|isbn=1555662374|pages=110\u2013112}}<!--|accessdate=5 February 2015--></ref> It is open to the public rental and for tours.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mollybrownsummerhouse.com/ Molly Brown Summer House]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080513030749/http://www.historicdistricts.com/CO/Denver/state.html National Register of Historic Places, Colorado, Denver]\n\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Denver]]\n[[Category:Houses in Denver]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Museums in Denver]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1897]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Colorado]]\n[[Category:James Joseph Brown family residences]]\n\n\n{{Colorado-museum-stub}}\n{{Colorado-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Denver-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zchwalz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Linked Brown to the sinking of the Titanic.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avoca_Lodge"}
